{"title_page": "Big Boss Man (wrestler)", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name                 = Big Boss Man\n| image                = Big Boss Man cropped.png\n| image_size           = 245px\n| caption              = Big Boss Man at a charity event in 2002\n| names                = Big Boss Man<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br />Boss Man<br/>Big Bubba<ref name=OWOW/><br/>Big Bubba Rogers<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br />The Boss<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br />The Guardian Angel<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br />The Man<br />Ray Traylor<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br />War Machine<ref name=OWOW/><ref name=Cage/>\n| height               = 6 ft 7 in<ref name=WWE/>\n| weight               = 330 lb<ref name=WWE/>\n| birth_date           = {{birth date|1963|5|2|mf=y}}\n| birth_place          = [[Marietta, Georgia]], [[United States of America|United States]] \n| death_date           = {{death date and age|2004|9|22|1963|5|2}}\n| death_place          = [[Dallas, Georgia]], United States \n| death_cause          = [[Myocardial infarction|Heart attack]]\n| spouse               = {{marriage|Angela Traylor|1989|}}\n| children             = 2\n| birth_name           = Ray Washington Traylor Jr. \n| billed               = [[Cobb County, Georgia]]<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n| trainer              = Ted Allen<ref name=OWOW>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/b/big-bossman/|title=Big Boss Man's OWOW profile|accessdate=November 20, 2009|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref name=Cage>[http://www.cagematch.de/?id=2&nr=690 Big Boss Man \u00ab Wrestler-Datenbank \u00ab CAGEMATCH \u2013 The Internet Wrestling Database]. Cagematch.de. Retrieved on November 20, 2016.</ref>\n| debut                = 1985\n| retired              = \n}}\n'''Ray Washington Traylor Jr.''' (May 2, 1963 \u2013 September 22, 2004)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgipage=pif&GRid=9507643&PIgrid=9507643&PIcrid=33532&ShowCemPhotos=Y& | publisher=Find A Grave | title= Millions of Cemetery Records and Online Memorials}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] who was best known for his appearances with the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) under the [[ring name]] '''Big Boss Man''', as well as for his appearances with [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) as '''The Boss''', '''The Man''', '''The Guardian Angel''', and '''Big Bubba Rogers'''. During his appearances with the WWF, Big Boss Man held the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF World Tag Team Championship]] [[list of World Tag Team Champions (WWE)|once]] and the [[WWE Hardcore Championship|WWF Hardcore Championship]] [[list of WWE Hardcore Champions|four times]].<ref name=\"WWE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/big-boss-man|title=Big Boss Man|publisher=[[WWE]]|work=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref> On March 7, 2016, Traylor was confirmed to be inducted into the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] Class of 2016.<ref name=\"WWE HOF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwe-hall-fame/article/big-boss-man-inducted-wwe-hall-fame-class-2016|title=Big Boss Man to be inducted into WWE Hall of Fame's Class of 2016|last=Pappolla|first=Ryan|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=March 7, 2016}}</ref> He was inducted in the [[WWE Hall of Fame|WWE]] Hall of Fame 2016 by [[Slick (wrestling)|Slick]] and the award was accepted by his wife Angela and his daughters Lacy and Megan.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n===Jim Crockett Promotions (1985\u20131987)===\nA former [[corrections officer]] in [[Cobb County, Georgia]], Traylor debuted in 1985. He first made some appearances at [[Continental Championship Wrestling]] where he first challenged Roberto Soto for the [[NWA Alabama Heavyweight Championship]] on February 3, 1986 and then challenged [[Norvell Austin]] for the [[NWA Southeastern Heavyweight Championship (Northern Division)|NWA Southeastern Heavyweight Championship]] on February 10.<ref name=\"Big Boss Man\">[https://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=690&page=4&s=1500 Big Boss Man] cagematch.net retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> He then began working as a [[job (professional wrestling)|jobber]] for [[Jim Crockett Promotions]], under his real name. During this time, he faced the likes of [[The Barbarian (wrestler)|The Barbarian]], [[Ivan Koloff]], [[The Midnight Express (professional wrestling)|The Midnight Express]], [[The Road Warriors]], and [[Wahoo McDaniel]].<ref name=\"JCP 1986\">[http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/jcp86.htm JCP 1986] thehistoryofwwe.com retrieved on May 4, 2019</ref> Seeing his potential, head booker [[Dusty Rhodes (wrestler)|Dusty Rhodes]] pulled Traylor from TV for 12 weeks, in order to repackage him as \"Big Bubba Rogers\" with Traylor debuting as Rogers on the May 31 edition of WorldWide.<ref name=\"JCP 1986\"/> As Big Bubba, Traylor was a silent [[bodyguard]] for [[Jim Cornette]], who, along with the [[The Midnight Express (professional wrestling)|Midnight Express]], was [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feuding]] with the James Boys (Dusty Rhodes and [[Magnum T.A.]], under masks). He got a solid [[push (professional wrestling)|push]] as a seemingly unstoppable [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] and feuded with Rhodes (the top [[Face (professional wrestling)|face]] at the time) in a series of [[Bunkhouse Stampede]] matches in 1986. He and Rhodes were tied for wins in this series, leading to a tiebreaking cage match, which Rhodes won on February 27.<ref>[http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/jcp87.htm JCP 1987] thehistoryofwwe.com retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> Traylor also defeated [[Ron Garvin]] in a Louisville Street Fight at [[Starrcade (1986)|Starrcade 1986]].\n\n===Universal Wrestling Federation (1987)===\nIn 1987, Traylor joined the [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Bill Watts)|Universal Wrestling Federation]] (UWF) after it was purchased by [[Jim Crockett Jr.|Jim Crockett]]. He debuted on April 18 winning a handicap match against Mike Reed and The Glassman.<ref name=\"Big Boss Man\"/> On April 19, Traylor challenged and won the [[UWF World Heavyweight Championship (Bill Watts)|UWF Heavyweight Championship]] from [[One Man Gang]], who was leaving the UWF for the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]]. Following his title win, he aligned himself with [[Skandor Ackbar|General Skandor Ackbar]] and his Devastation Inc. stable.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=diMbZ5jZYf8 UWF 2 5 87] youtube.com retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> Traylor would hold the championship for nearly 3 months defending it against [[Steve Cox (wrestler)|Steve Cox]], [[Barry Windham]], and [[Michael Hayes (wrestler)|Michael Hayes]]<ref name=\"Big Boss Man\"/> before losing the title to [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams]] on July 11, 1987 in Oklahoma City, OK during the [[Great American Bash (1987)|Great American Bash 1987]] tour.<ref>[https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=141747 NWA Great American Bash Tour 1987 - Tag 10] cagematch.net retrieved May 4, 2019</ref>\n\nIn the second [[WarGames match]] on July 30, 1987, [[The Road Warriors]], [[Nikita Koloff]], [[Dusty Rhodes (wrestler)|Dusty Rhodes]], and [[Paul Ellering]] defeated [[The Four Horsemen (professional wrestling)|The Four Horsemen]] and Traylor as '''The War Machine''' at 19:38 when [[Road Warrior Animal]] forced the War Machine to submit by gouging his eyes with a spiked armband.\n\nAfter losing the heavyweight championship, Traylor began pursuing the [[UWF Tag Team Championship]] which were held by [[The Lightning Express (professional wrestling)|The Lightning Express]] as he teamed with [[The Angel of Death (wrestler)|The Angel of Death]], [[The Terminator (wrestler)|The Terminator]], and [[Black Bart (wrestler)|Black Bart]] but was never able to win the titles.<ref name=\"cagematch.net\">[https://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=690&page=4&s=1400 Big Boss Man] cagematch.net retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> From late August to early September, Traylor received several rematches against Williams for the UWF Championship but came up short.<ref name=\"cagematch.net\"/>\n\n===All Japan Pro Wrestling (1988)===\nAfter leaving Crockett, Traylor toured for [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]] during their 1988 Champion Carnival tour. He debuted on March 26, 1988, teaming with [[Bruiser Brody]] against [[Jumbo Tsuruta]] and [[John Tenta]] which went to a double countout. Throughout the tour, Traylor would mostly team with Brody as well as [[Jimmy Snuka]] while taking on stars like Tsuruta, [[Genichiro Tenryu]], [[Yoshiaki Yatsu]], [[Giant Baba]], and [[Ashura Hara]] as well as future stars like [[Mitsuharu Misawa|Tiger Mask]] and [[Akira Taue]]. His last match was the conclusion of the tour on April 22 losing to Tsuruta.<ref>[http://www.purolove.com/ajpw/results/88carnival.php All Japan Pro Wrestling - \"Champion Carnival 1988\"] purolove.com retrieved May 4, 2019</ref>\n\n===World Wrestling Federation===\n==== Twin Towers (1988&ndash;1990) ====\n{{main|The Twin Towers (professional wrestling)|l1=Twin Towers}}\nIn June 1988, Traylor joined the WWF as \"Big Boss Man\", a character inspired by his previous career as a corrections officer. Wrestling as a heel and managed by [[Slick (wrestling)|Slick]], Boss Man's post-match routine often included handcuffing his defeated opponents to the ring ropes and beating them with a nightstick or ball and chain.\n\nAfter defeating [[Koko B. Ware]] at [[SummerSlam (1988)|the inaugural SummerSlam]], Boss Man began his first major WWF angle by attacking [[Hulk Hogan]] on [[Bruce Prichard#Brother Love Show|\"The Brother Love Show\"]]. During this feud, he also challenged [[Randy Poffo|Randy Savage]] for the [[WWE World Heavyweight Championship|WWF Championship]], and formed a team with [[One Man Gang|Akeem]] (formerly billed as One Man Gang, his UWF opponent) to form [[The Twin Towers (professional wrestling)|The Twin Towers]]. They feuded with Hogan and Savage (who had formed [[The Mega Powers]]), and were a key part in the top storyline of Savage turning on Hogan, leading to the [[WrestleMania V]] main event; in the later part of a tag match between the four on ''[[The Main Event II]]'', Hogan abandoned Savage to attend to the hurt [[Miss Elizabeth]] and went backstage. After being double-teamed for a while, Savage eventually rallied until Hogan returned to the match. After Savage tagged Hogan in, he slapped Hogan and left him to defeat The Twin Towers on his own. This led to The Mega Powers' demise as Savage beat Hulk in the backstage medical room where fellow wrestlers, managers and staff had to break them up.\n\nAt WrestleMania V, The Twin Towers defeated [[The Rockers]] ([[Shawn Michaels]] and [[Marty Jannetty]]) and then, for most of spring and early summer 1989, feuded with [[Demolition (professional wrestling)|Demolition]] ([[Bill Eadie|Ax]] and [[Barry Darsow|Smash]]) over the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|Tag Team Championship]]. Meanwhile, Boss Man concluded his feud with Hogan in a series of [[Steel Cage match]]es; one of the most memorable aired on the May 27 ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event XXI]]'', with Hogan's WWF Championship on the line. During the match, Hogan [[superplex]]ed Boss Man off the top of the cage.\n\n[[File:Big Bossman and Slick.jpg|thumb|right|Boss Man became a [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]] after he refused to do the bidding of his villainous manager [[Slick (wrestling)|Slick]] (left)]]\nThe Big Boss Man turned [[Face (professional wrestling)|face]] on the February 24, 1990 episode of ''[[WWF Superstars|Superstars]]'', when [[Ted DiBiase]] had paid Slick to have Boss Man retrieve the [[Million Dollar Championship]] belt from [[Jake Roberts]], who had stolen it. Boss Man retrieved a bag containing both the belt and Roberts' pet python, Damien. On ''[[Brother Love (wrestler)|The Brother Love Show]]'', he refused to accept DiBiase's money for the bag, and returned it to Roberts.<ref>{{Citation|last=|title=WWF History \u2013 Big Boss Man (from heel to face) YouTube video|date=March 17, 2008|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wsK_EJuE_a4|accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBoss Man then feuded with former partner Akeem, defeating him in [[Squash (professional wrestling)|less than two minutes]] at [[WrestleMania VI]]. As part of his face turn, he later stopped handcuffing and beating jobbers after matches. He made peace with Hogan, appearing in his corner in his match against [[John Tenta|Earthquake]] at Summerslam 1990, and teaming with him at the [[Survivor Series (1990)|1990 Survivor Series]], along with [[Jim Duggan|\"Hacksaw\" Jim Duggan]] and [[Fred Ottman|Tugboat]], to defeat Earthquake's team.\n\n==== Singles competition (1990&ndash;1993) ====\nIn the fall of 1990, Boss Man began feuding with [[Bobby Heenan]] and [[The Heenan Family]] after Heenan continually insulted Boss Man's mother. He won a series of matches against Heenan Family members in 1991, including [[Sione Vailahi|The Barbarian]] at the [[Royal Rumble (1991)|Royal Rumble]] and [[Curt Hennig|Mr. Perfect]] (via disqualification) at [[WrestleMania VII]] in an [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]] match, which featured the return of [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]]. At [[SummerSlam (1991)|SummerSlam]], he defeated [[Jacques Rougeau|The Mountie]] in a Jailhouse Match, a match in which the loser must spend a night in jail. This was the only such match ever held by the promotion. Boss Man then briefly feuded with [[Mike Rotunda|Irwin R. Schyster]].\n\nIn 1992, Boss Man began feuding with [[Kevin Wacholz|Nailz]], an ex-convict character who, in a series of promos aired before his debut, claimed Boss Man had been his abusive Officer in prison, and warned he was seeking revenge. On the May 30 episode of ''[[WWF Superstars]]'', Nailz \u2013 clad in an orange prison jumpsuit \u2013 ran into the ring and attacked Boss Man, handcuffing him to the top rope and repeatedly choking and beating him with the nightstick. Boss Man took time off TV to sell his ([[kayfabe]]) injuries, eventually returning and having a series of matches with Nailz in the latter half of 1992. The feud culminated at [[Survivor Series (1992)|Survivor Series]], when Boss Man defeated Nailz in a [[Professional wrestling match types#(Object) on a Pole match|Nightstick on a Pole match]]. This was the final push for the Boss Man during this run, as he was subsequently used as [[enhancement talent]] against [[Scott Hall|Razor Ramon]], [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], and [[Yokozuna (wrestler)|Yokozuna]] on the house show circuit.\n\nThe Big Boss Man's last [[pay-per-view]] match of this run came at the [[Royal Rumble (1993)|1993 Royal Rumble]], where he lost to [[Bam Bam Bigelow]]. He left the WWF shortly after a [[house show]] in [[Gatineau, Quebec]] defeating [[Doink the Clown]] on March 14.<ref>[http://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=104&bild=1&details=7&liga=3&jahr=1993&seite=2 Big Boss Man's 1993 WWF matches, from]. WrestlingData.com. Retrieved on November 20, 2016.</ref> During the next few months he made appearances in the USWA and SMW. On December 4 he made a one-time return to the WWF as a special guest referee to officiate the main event of a house show in Anaheim, California between Bret Hart and Jeff Jarrett. Boss Man was expected to rejoin the WWF but elected to sign with WCW instead.<ref>[http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/93.htm 1993]. thehistoryofwwe.com</ref>\n\n===Return to All Japan Pro Wrestling (1993)===\nTraylor returned to All Japan in 1993. Due to not owning the Big Boss Man gimmick, he again used his \"Big Bubba\" name but still wore the Big Boss Man attire and carried the nightstick. He returned on July 2 defeating Mighty Inoue in a little over three minutes.<ref>[http://www.purolove.com/ajpw/results/93summeraction.php All Japan Pro Wrestling - \"Summer Action Series 1993\"] purolove.com retrieved on May 4, 2019</ref> As was the case with his previous run, he mainly worked tag matches, often with [[Stan Hansen]], [[Kendall Windham]] or \"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams, but also defeated Mighty Inoue, [[John Hindley|Johnny Smith]] and [[Tamon Honda]] in singles matches. He also had some big one-on-one matches as he lost to Akira Taue on July 29 at the [[Nippon Budokan]]<ref>[https://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=690&page=4&s=1400 AJPW Summer Action Series 1993 - Tag 22] cagematch.net retrieved May 19, 2019</ref> and lost to [[Kenta Kobashi]] on October 14.<ref>[https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=63063 AJPW October Giant Series 1993 - Tag 13] cagematch.net retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> From November to December, Traylor competed in the 1993 [[World's Strongest Tag Determination League#1993|World's Strongest Tag Determination League]] teaming with Williams where they placed 4th.<ref>[http://www.purolove.com/ajpw/history/rwtl93.php Real World Tag League 1993] purolove.com retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> His last match was on the end of the tour on December 3 teaming with Williams in a losing effort to Giant Baba and Stan Hansen.\n\n===World Championship Wrestling===\n==== Early years (1993&ndash;1995) ====\n{{Unreferenced section|date= September 2015}}\nTraylor returned to the United States to debut for [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW), as \"The Boss\", on the December 18, 1993 episode of ''[[WCW Saturday Night]]'', pinning the International World Champion, [[Rick Rude]], in a non-title match. A face, he received a title match against Rude at [[Starrcade (1993)|Starrcade '93: 10th Anniversary]], but lost. In light of legal complaints from the WWF regarding the similarity of \"The Boss\" to \"Big Boss Man\", Traylor was renamed \"The Guardian Angel\", and wore similar attire to those in the [[Guardian Angels|organization he was named after]]. He feuded with [[Big Van Vader]] for most of 1994. In early 1995, he turned heel, and became again known as \"Big Bubba Rogers\". He defeated [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]] at [[Uncensored 1995|Uncensored]] in 1995.\n\n==== Dungeon of Doom and feud with nWo (1996&ndash;1998) ====\nIn 1996, Rogers joined [[The Dungeon of Doom]]. He feuded with former Dungeon of Doom member [[John Tenta]], and newcomer [[Glacier (wrestler)|Glacier]]. By the end of the year, he had turned on the Dungeon of Doom and joined the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|nWo]]. His stay in the nWo was brief, with Traylor knocked out by an unknown assailant at the start of the February 17, 1997 edition of Nitro, with Traylor later explaining Eric Bischoff fired him from the nWo while he was temporarily paralyzed.  Traylor returned on September 1, now using his real name and vowing to rip Bischoff's head off. He feuded with the nWo, defeating members such as [[Scott Hall (wrestler)|Scott Hall]], Curt Hennig, and [[Mike Jones (wrestler)|Vincent]]. He formed an alliance with [[The Steiner Brothers]], who also sought DiBiase as their manager. The union abruptly ended when Scott Steiner turned on them to join the nWo in February 1998. After losing his final WCW Nitro match to [[Bill Goldberg]] on the March 30 episode of ''[[WCW Nitro|Nitro]]'', Traylor won his final match defeating Bret Hammer on the following ''Saturday Night'' after that he was sent home and WCW let his contract expire.\n\n===Return to WWF/E===\n====Hardcore Championship pursuit (1998&ndash;2000)====\n{{See also|The Corporation (professional wrestling)|l1=The Corporation}}\n[[File:1999 Big Bossman WWF Smackdown (WWE).jpg|thumb|220px|Big Boss Man on ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'' in 1999]]\nTraylor rejoined the WWF shortly after his WCW release and once again became \"Big Boss Man\". On October 12, 1998, he returned to television with a new look, abandoning his blue police shirt for an all-black [[SWAT]]-style uniform, including a tactical vest and gloves. He served as [[Vince McMahon]]'s bodyguard during his feud with [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]] and his later feud with [[D-Generation X]]. He briefly wore a mask, before his identity was revealed.\n\nBoss Man was one of the first members of McMahon's heel stable, [[The Corporation (professional wrestling)|The Corporation]], and served as a bodyguard for other members, such as Vince's son [[Shane McMahon|Shane]]. While in The Corporation, Boss Man won the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|Tag Team Championship]] with [[Ken Shamrock]], won the [[WWE Hardcore Championship|Hardcore Championship]] four times, and lost to [[The Undertaker]] at [[WrestleMania XV]] in a [[Hell in a Cell]] match. After this match, [[The Undertaker]] hanged him from the roof of the cage (an illusion made possible by a body harness concealed under Traylor's outfit).\n\nIn the WWF's Hardcore division, Boss Man's major feud was with [[Al Snow]], a feud that eventually involved Snow's pet chihuahua, Pepper. At [[SummerSlam (1999)|SummerSlam]], the two had a Falls Count Anywhere match that spilled into the backstage area, the street and, finally, into a nearby bar. Just prior to the match, Snow had set Pepper's [[pet carrier]] near the entranceway. Minutes into the match, Boss Man picked it up, taunted Pepper, struck Snow with the carrier and carelessly tossed it behind him. Commentator [[Jim Ross]] immediately apologized to viewers for the act, and stated that Pepper had been removed from the box before the match.\n\nTwo weeks later, Boss Man kidnapped and ransomed Pepper, arranging a meeting in which he fed Snow a meat dish supposedly made from Pepper's remains. The two settled their feud in a [[Hell in a Cell#Legacy|Kennel from Hell match]] at [[Unforgiven (1999)|Unforgiven]], in which a blue solid steel cage surrounded the ring, itself and ringside surrounded by the chain-link fenced \"cell\". The object of the match was to escape from the cage and the cell while avoiding \"attack dogs\" (which turned out to be disappointingly docile) positioned outside the ring. Snow won the match and retained the Hardcore title, which had been returned to him by [[Davey Boy Smith]], who had defeated Boss Man for it.  Boss Man would later win back the Hardcore title in a triple threat match involving [[Al Snow]] and [[Paul Wight|The Big Show]], and would hold it until January 2000, when he lost it to [[Test (wrestler)|Test]].\n\nBoss Man then feuded with [[Paul Wight|The Big Show]] over the [[WWE World Heavyweight Championship|WWF Championship]]. During the feud, Boss Man showed up at Big Show's father's funeral, made some disrespectful remarks, then chained the casket to the back of his car and drove off. The Big Show attempted to save the coffin by jumping on it, riding it for a few yards before losing his grip and tumbling off, the feud also included a segment in which Boss Man invaded the home of Big Show's mother and forced her on camera to admit her son was born an [[Legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]] child. Boss Man became the #1 contender for the WWF Championship by defeating [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] on the November 15, 1999 episode of ''Raw''. At [[Armageddon (1999)|Armageddon]], The Big Show defeated him to retain the title and end the feud.\n\n==== Various feuds and departure (2000&ndash;2003) ====\nBoss Man entered the [[Royal Rumble (2000)|2000 Royal Rumble match]], where he eliminated [[Solofa Fatu|Rikishi]] (with the help of five other wrestlers), [[Chyna]] and [[Ron Simmons|Faarooq]], before being eliminated by The Rock.\n\nOn the March 19 episode of ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'', he introduced [[Barry Buchanan|Bull Buchanan]] as his prot\u00e9g\u00e9. They teamed to defeat [[Charles Wright (wrestler)|The Godfather]] and [[D'Lo Brown]] at [[WrestleMania 2000]], and the [[Acolytes Protection Agency]] the next month at [[Backlash (2000)|Backlash]]. On the June 5 ''Raw is War'', after losing to [[The Hardy Boyz]] and subsequently arguing, Boss Man knocked Buchanan out with his nightstick when his back was turned and the team split up.\n\nIn the summer of 2000, Boss Man disappeared from the WWF's primary television shows, wrestling mainly on ''[[WWF Jakked/Metal|Jakked]]'' and ''Heat'', where he had a minor feud with [[Crash Holly]] until suffering a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#L|legit]] injury in January 2001. When he returned on the December 20, 2001 of ''SmackDown!'', he formed a team with [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]], after Vince McMahon ordered him to be Booker's enforcer. On the December 27 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Boss Man and Booker T defeated Stone Cold Steve Austin in a handicap match. On the January 7, 2002 episode of ''Raw'', Boss Man and Booker T were defeated by Austin and The Rock. On the January 17 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Boss Man lost to Diamond Dallas Page. At the [[Royal Rumble (2002)|Royal Rumble]], Boss Man competed in the Royal Rumble match where he was eliminated by [[Rikishi (wrestler)|Rikishi]]. On the January 24 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Boss Man lost to Rikishi. The team quietly split in late January 2002, and Boss Man returned to ''Jakked/Metal'' and ''Heat''. On the February 2 episode of ''Metal'', Boss Man defeated [[Gregory Helms|The Hurricane]]. On the February 9 episode of ''Metal'', Boss Man defeated [[Perry Saturn]]. On the March 23 episode of ''[[WWF Jakked/Metal|WWF Jakked]]'', Boss Man and Mr. Perfect lost to [[The Acolytes Protection Agency|The APA]]. In April, he formed a short-lived tag team with [[Curt Hennig|Mr. Perfect]] after both were [[WWE Draft|drafted]] to the Raw [[WWE Brand Extension|brand]]. On the April 1 episode of ''Raw'', Boss Man and Mr. Perfect lost to [[The Hardy Boyz]]. On the April 14 episode of ''Heat'', Boss Man lost to Bradshaw. On the April 28 episode of ''Heat'', Boss Man defeated [[Crash Holly]]. On the May 12 episode of ''Heat'', Boss Man lost to [[D'Lo Brown]]. On the May 26 episode of ''Heat'', he lost his final WWE match to [[Tommy Dreamer]].\n\nTraylor was assigned to train developmental wrestlers in [[Ohio Valley Wrestling]], before being released from WWE in 2003.\n\n===International Wrestling Association of Japan (2004)===\nTraylor's final matches were in the [[International Wrestling Association of Japan]], where he competed in a tournament for the vacant [[IWA World Heavyweight Championship (IWA Japan)|IWA World Heavyweight Championship]]. He made it to the final by defeating [[Doug Gilbert|Freddie Krueger]] before losing to [[Jim Duggan]].<ref name=Wrestlingdata>{{cite web|title=Big Boss Man|url=http://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=104|accessdate=November 19, 2013|publisher=Wrestlingdata}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTraylor had two daughters, Lacy Abilene Traylor and Megan Chyanne Traylor, and was married to Angela, his childhood sweetheart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/tremendous-tirades-special-rip-ray-traylor/ |title=Tremendous Tirades Special: RIP Ray Traylor |author=Csonka, Larry |date=September 24, 2004 |website=411mania.com |publisher= |accessdate= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035109/http://411mania.com/wrestling/tremendous-tirades-special-rip-ray-traylor/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTraylor suffered a huge motorcycle accident on his Harley-Davidson in May 2002 after he hit a deer, and was badly injured. He spent a year recovering from his injuries, and he was badly affected by close friend [[Curt Hennig]]'s death in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-VgEhLfEpiQ&t=278s|title=Bruce Prichard Shoots on The Death of Big Boss Man|publisher=[[YouTube]].com|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2004, Traylor ran for Commission chairman for [[Paulding County, Georgia]].<ref name=\"Oliver\">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2004/09/24/642381.html|title=Friends remember Big Bossman\t|author=Oliver, Greg|publisher=[[Qu\u00e9becor M\u00e9dia]]|work=[[Canoe.ca]]|date=September 24, 2004|accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://paulding.com/forum/index.php/topic/11151-ray-traylor-big-boss-man/ IN MEMORY OF RAY TRAYLOR \u2013 \"The Big Boss Man\", by Tammy L. Fincham]. Paulding.com. Retrieved on November 20, 2016.</ref> He was the owner of a [[Dallas, Georgia]] storage company called RWT Enterprises.<ref>[http://www.chamberofcommerce.com/dallas-ga/27649226-rwt-enterprises-inc/ RWT Enterprises profile at]. Chamberofcommerce.com. Retrieved on November 20, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Death and legacy===\nTraylor died of a heart attack on September 22, 2004, aged 41 at his home in [[Dallas, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Clevett|first=Jason|title=Ray \"Big Bossman\" Traylor passes away|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2004/09/23/639653.html|accessdate=September 14, 2015|publisher=Canoe Slam}}</ref> He was posthumously inducted into the WWE Hall of Fame in 2016, with his wife and daughters accepting the award on his behalf.\n\nBig Boss Man appears in video games including ''[[WWF WrestleMania 2000]]'', ''[[WWF SmackDown! 2: Know Your Role]]'' and ''[[WWF No Mercy]]''. He further appears posthumously in ''[[WWE Legends of WrestleMania]]'', ''[[WWE All Stars]]'', ''[[WWE '13]]'', ''[[WWE 2K16]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/inside/2k/wwe-2k16/wwe-2k16-roster-playable-characters-superstars-divas|title=Superstars and Divas featured on WWE 2K16 roster list|publisher=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WWE 2K17]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k17/article/wwe-2k17-roster-playable-characters-superstars|title=Superstars to be featured on WWE 2K17 roster|publisher=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WWE 2K18]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k18/article/wwe-2k18-roster-playable-character-list|title=WWE 2K18 roster: Meet the Superstars joining the list of playable characters|publisher=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WWE 2K19]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwe.2k.com/roster/wwe-2k19|title=WWE 2K19 Roster|publisher=[[WWE 2K]]|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref> and in ''[[WWE 2K20]]''.\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**Ranked #'''23''' of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 1992<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi50092.htm|accessdate=August 3, 2009|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Top 500 \u2013 1992|publisher=Wrestling Information Archive|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813033929/http://100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi50092.htm|archivedate=August 13, 2011}}</ref>\n**PWI ranked him #'''138''' of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the \"PWI Years\" in 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi500yr.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 5, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707054220/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi500yr.htm |archivedate=July 7, 2011 }}</ref>\n*'''[[Superstars of Wrestling|Pro Wrestling This Week]]'''\n**Wrestler of the Week (May 3\u20139, 1987)<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Pro Wrestling This Week |url= |access-date= |series=[[Superstars of Wrestling]] |first=Joe |last=Pedicino |authorlink=Joe Pedicino |first2=Gordon (hosts) |last2=Solie |author2link=Gordon Solie |network=[[Broadcast syndication|Syndicated]] |station=[[WATL]] |location=[[Atlanta, Georgia]] |date=May 9, 1987 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n*'''[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Bill Watts)|Universal Wrestling Federation]]'''\n**[[UWF Heavyweight Championship]] ([[UWF Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>[http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/whtuwf.html Solie's Title Histories:UWF \u2013 UNIVERSAL WRESTLING FEDERATION]. Solie.org (May 30, 1986). Retrieved on November 20, 2016.</ref>\n*'''[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/WWE]]'''\n**[[WWE Hardcore Championship|WWF Hardcore Championship]] ([[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|4 times]])<ref>[http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/hard/ Hardcore Championship]. Wwe.com (November 16, 2016). Retrieved on November 20, 2016.</ref>\n**[[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of World Tag Team Champions (WWE)|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Ken Shamrock]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/worldtagteam/3044541321211112 | title=Big Boss Man & Ken Shamrock | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051129092420/http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/worldtagteam/3044541321211112 | archivedate=November 29, 2005 | accessdate=December 17, 2016 | publisher=[[WWE]] | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n**[[WWE Hall of Fame]] (Class of 2016)<ref name=\"WWE HOF\" />\n*'''''[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'''''\n**[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Most Improved|Most Improved]] (1987)\n**[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Feud|Worst Feud of the Year]] (1996) <small>vs. John Tenta</small>\n**[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Feud|Worst Feud of the Year]] (1999) <small>vs. The Big Show</small>\n**[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Match|Worst Worked Match of the Year]] (1999) <small>vs. Al Snow at [[Unforgiven (1999)|Unforgiven]]</small>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of premature professional wrestling deaths]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ray Traylor}}\n*{{wwe superstar|big-boss-man|Big Boss Man}}\n*{{IMDb name|0871498|Ray Traylor}}\n*{{findagrave|9507643|Ray Traylor}}\n\n{{WWE Hardcore Championship}}\n{{World Tag Team Championship (WWE)}}\n{{The Streak}}\n{{New World Order}}\n{{WWE Hall of Fame}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Big Boss Man}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:The Corporate Ministry members]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Marietta, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling managers and valets]]\n[[Category:The New World Order (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:WWE Hall of Fame inductees]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestler}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name                 = Big Boss Man\n| image                = Big Boss Man cropped.png\n| image_size           = 245px\n| caption              = Big Boss Man at a charity event in 2002\n| names                = Big Boss Man<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br />Boss Man<br/>Big Bubba<ref name=OWOW/><br/>Big Bubba Rogers<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br />The Boss<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br />The Guardian Angel<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br />The Man<br />Ray Traylor<ref name=\"WWE\"/><br />War Machine<ref name=OWOW/><ref name=Cage/>\n| height               = 6 ft 7 in<ref name=WWE/>\n| weight               = 330 lb<ref name=WWE/>\n| birth_date           = {{birth date|1963|5|2|mf=y}}\n| birth_place          = [[Marietta, Georgia]], [[United States of America|United States]] \n| death_date           = {{death date and age|2004|9|22|1963|5|2}}\n| death_place          = [[Dallas, Georgia]], United States \n| death_cause          = [[Myocardial infarction|Heart attack]]\n| spouse               = {{marriage|Angela Traylor|1989|}}\n| children             = 2\n| birth_name           = Ray Washington Traylor Jr. \n| billed               = [[Cobb County, Georgia]]<ref name=\"WWE\"/>\n| trainer              = Ted Allen<ref name=OWOW>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/bios/b/big-bossman/|title=Big Boss Man's OWOW profile|accessdate=November 20, 2009|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><ref name=Cage>[http://www.cagematch.de/?id=2&nr=690 Big Boss Man \u00ab Wrestler-Datenbank \u00ab CAGEMATCH \u2013 The Internet Wrestling Database]. Cagematch.de. Retrieved on November 20, 2016.</ref>\n| debut                = 1985\n| retired              = \n}}\n'''Ray Washington Traylor Jr.''' (May 2, 1963 \u2013 September 22, 2004)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgipage=pif&GRid=9507643&PIgrid=9507643&PIcrid=33532&ShowCemPhotos=Y& | publisher=Find A Grave | title= Millions of Cemetery Records and Online Memorials}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] who was best known for his appearances with the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) under the [[ring name]] '''Big Boss Man''', as well as for his appearances with [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) as '''The Boss''', '''The Man''', '''The Guardian Angel''', and '''Big Bubba Rogers'''. During his appearances with the WWF, Big Boss Man held the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF World Tag Team Championship]] [[list of World Tag Team Champions (WWE)|once]] and the [[WWE Hardcore Championship|WWF Hardcore Championship]] [[list of WWE Hardcore Champions|four times]].<ref name=\"WWE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/big-boss-man|title=Big Boss Man|publisher=[[WWE]]|work=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref> On March 7, 2016, Traylor was confirmed to be inducted into the [[WWE Hall of Fame]] Class of 2016.<ref name=\"WWE HOF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwe-hall-fame/article/big-boss-man-inducted-wwe-hall-fame-class-2016|title=Big Boss Man to be inducted into WWE Hall of Fame's Class of 2016|last=Pappolla|first=Ryan|date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=March 7, 2016}}</ref> He was inducted in the [[WWE Hall of Fame|WWE]] Hall of Fame 2016 by [[Slick (wrestling)|Slick]] and the award was accepted by his wife Angela and his daughters Lacy and Megan.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n===Jim Crockett Promotions (1985\u20131987)===\nA former [[corrections officer]] in [[Cobb County, Georgia]], Traylor debuted in 1985. He first made some appearances at [[Continental Championship Wrestling]] where he first challenged Roberto Soto for the [[NWA Alabama Heavyweight Championship]] on February 3, 1986 and then challenged [[Norvell Austin]] for the [[NWA Southeastern Heavyweight Championship (Northern Division)|NWA Southeastern Heavyweight Championship]] on February 10.<ref name=\"Big Boss Man\">[https://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=690&page=4&s=1500 Big Boss Man] cagematch.net retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> He then began working as a [[job (professional wrestling)|jobber]] for [[Jim Crockett Promotions]], under his real name. During this time, he faced the likes of [[The Barbarian (wrestler)|The Barbarian]], [[Ivan Koloff]], [[The Midnight Express (professional wrestling)|The Midnight Express]], [[The Road Warriors]], and [[Wahoo McDaniel]].<ref name=\"JCP 1986\">[http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/jcp86.htm JCP 1986] thehistoryofwwe.com retrieved on May 4, 2019</ref> Seeing his potential, head booker [[Dusty Rhodes (wrestler)|Dusty Rhodes]] pulled Traylor from TV for 12 weeks, in order to repackage him as \"Big Bubba Rogers\" with Traylor debuting as Rogers on the May 31 edition of WorldWide.<ref name=\"JCP 1986\"/> As Big Bubba, Traylor was a silent [[bodyguard]] for [[Jim Cornette]], who, along with the [[The Midnight Express (professional wrestling)|Midnight Express]], was [[Feud (professional wrestling)|feuding]] with the James Boys (Dusty Rhodes and [[Magnum T.A.]], under masks). He got a solid [[push (professional wrestling)|push]] as a seemingly unstoppable [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] and feuded with Rhodes (the top [[Face (professional wrestling)|face]] at the time) in a series of [[Bunkhouse Stampede|bunkhouse stampede]] matches in 1986. He and Rhodes were tied for wins in this series, leading to a tiebreaking cage match, which Rhodes won on February 27.<ref>[http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/jcp87.htm JCP 1987] thehistoryofwwe.com retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> Traylor also defeated [[Ron Garvin]] in a Louisville Street Fight at [[Starrcade (1986)|Starrcade 1986]].\n\n===Universal Wrestling Federation (1987)===\nIn 1987, Traylor joined the [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Bill Watts)|Universal Wrestling Federation]] (UWF) after it was purchased by [[Jim Crockett Jr.|Jim Crockett]]. He debuted on April 18 winning a handicap match against Mike Reed and The Glassman.<ref name=\"Big Boss Man\"/> On April 19, Traylor challenged and won the [[UWF World Heavyweight Championship (Bill Watts)|UWF Heavyweight Championship]] from [[One Man Gang]], who was leaving the UWF for the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]]. Following his title win, he aligned himself with [[Skandor Ackbar|General Skandor Ackbar]] and his Devastation Inc. stable.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=diMbZ5jZYf8 UWF 2 5 87] youtube.com retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> Traylor would hold the championship for nearly 3 months defending it against [[Steve Cox (wrestler)|Steve Cox]], [[Barry Windham]], and [[Michael Hayes (wrestler)|Michael Hayes]]<ref name=\"Big Boss Man\"/> before losing the title to [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams]] on July 11, 1987 in Oklahoma City, OK during the [[Great American Bash (1987)|Great American Bash 1987]] tour.<ref>[https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=141747 NWA Great American Bash Tour 1987 - Tag 10] cagematch.net retrieved May 4, 2019</ref>\n\nIn the second [[WarGames match]] on July 30, 1987, [[The Road Warriors]], [[Nikita Koloff]], [[Dusty Rhodes (wrestler)|Dusty Rhodes]], and [[Paul Ellering]] defeated [[The Four Horsemen (professional wrestling)|The Four Horsemen]] and Traylor as '''The War Machine''' at 19:38 when [[Road Warrior Animal]] forced the War Machine to submit by gouging his eyes with a spiked armband.\n\nAfter losing the heavyweight championship, Traylor began pursuing the [[UWF Tag Team Championship]] which were held by [[The Lightning Express (professional wrestling)|The Lightning Express]] as he teamed with [[The Angel of Death (wrestler)|The Angel of Death]], [[The Terminator (wrestler)|The Terminator]], and [[Black Bart (wrestler)|Black Bart]] but was never able to win the titles.<ref name=\"cagematch.net\">[https://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=690&page=4&s=1400 Big Boss Man] cagematch.net retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> From late August to early September, Traylor received several rematches against Williams for the UWF Championship but came up short.<ref name=\"cagematch.net\"/>\n\n===All Japan Pro Wrestling (1988)===\nAfter leaving Crockett, Traylor toured for [[All Japan Pro Wrestling]] during their 1988 Champion Carnival tour. He debuted on March 26, 1988, teaming with [[Bruiser Brody]] against [[Jumbo Tsuruta]] and [[John Tenta]] which went to a double countout. Throughout the tour, Traylor would mostly team with Brody as well as [[Jimmy Snuka]] while taking on stars like Tsuruta, [[Genichiro Tenryu]], [[Yoshiaki Yatsu]], [[Giant Baba]], and [[Ashura Hara]] as well as future stars like [[Mitsuharu Misawa|Tiger Mask]] and [[Akira Taue]]. His last match was the conclusion of the tour on April 22 losing to Tsuruta.<ref>[http://www.purolove.com/ajpw/results/88carnival.php All Japan Pro Wrestling - \"Champion Carnival 1988\"] purolove.com retrieved May 4, 2019</ref>\n\n===World Wrestling Federation===\n==== Twin Towers (1988&ndash;1990) ====\n{{main|The Twin Towers (professional wrestling)|l1=Twin Towers}}\nIn June 1988, Traylor joined the WWF as \"Big Boss Man\", a character inspired by his previous career as a corrections officer. Wrestling as a heel and managed by [[Slick (wrestling)|Slick]], Boss Man's post-match routine often included handcuffing his defeated opponents to the ring ropes and beating them with a nightstick or ball and chain.\n\nAfter defeating [[Koko B. Ware]] at [[SummerSlam (1988)|the inaugural SummerSlam]], Boss Man began his first major WWF angle by attacking [[Hulk Hogan]] on [[Bruce Prichard#Brother Love Show|\"The Brother Love Show\"]]. During this feud, he also challenged [[Randy Poffo|Randy Savage]] for the [[WWE World Heavyweight Championship|WWF Championship]], and formed a team with [[One Man Gang|Akeem]] (formerly billed as One Man Gang, his UWF opponent) to form [[The Twin Towers (professional wrestling)|The Twin Towers]]. They feuded with Hogan and Savage (who had formed [[The Mega Powers]]), and were a key part in the top storyline of Savage turning on Hogan, leading to the [[WrestleMania V]] main event; in the later part of a tag match between the four on ''[[The Main Event II]]'', Hogan abandoned Savage to attend to the hurt [[Miss Elizabeth]] and went backstage. After being double-teamed for a while, Savage eventually rallied until Hogan returned to the match. After Savage tagged Hogan in, he slapped Hogan and left him to defeat The Twin Towers on his own. This led to The Mega Powers' demise as Savage beat Hulk in the backstage medical room where fellow wrestlers, managers and staff had to break them up.\n\nAt WrestleMania V, The Twin Towers defeated [[The Rockers]] ([[Shawn Michaels]] and [[Marty Jannetty]])  and then, for most of spring and early summer 1989, feuded with [[Demolition (professional wrestling)|Demolition]] ([[Bill Eadie|Ax]] and [[Barry Darsow|Smash]]) over the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|Tag Team Championship]]. Meanwhile, Boss Man concluded his feud with Hogan in a series of [[Steel Cage match|steel cage matches]]; one of the most memorable aired on the May 27 ''[[Saturday Night's Main Event XXI]]'', with Hogan's WWF Championship on the line. During the match, Hogan [[superplex]]ed Boss Man off the top of the cage.\n\n[[File:Big Bossman and Slick.jpg|thumb|right|Boss Man became a [[Face (professional wrestling)|fan favorite]] after he refused to do the bidding of his villainous manager [[Slick (wrestling)|Slick]] (left)]]\nThe Big Boss Man turned [[Face (professional wrestling)|face]] on the February 24, 1990 episode of ''[[WWF Superstars|Superstars]]'', when [[Ted DiBiase]] had paid Slick to have Boss Man retrieve the [[Million Dollar Championship]] belt from [[Jake Roberts]], who had stolen it. Boss Man retrieved a bag containing both the belt and Roberts' pet python, Damien. On ''[[Brother Love (wrestler)|The Brother Love Show]]'', he refused to accept DiBiase's money for the bag, and returned it to Roberts.<ref>{{Citation|last=|title=WWF History \u2013 Big Boss Man (from heel to face) YouTube video|date=March 17, 2008|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wsK_EJuE_a4|accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBoss Man then feuded with former partner Akeem, defeating him in [[Squash (professional wrestling)|less than two minutes]] at [[WrestleMania VI]]. As part of his face turn, he later stopped handcuffing and beating jobbers after matches. He made peace with Hogan, appearing in his corner in his match against [[John Tenta|Earthquake]] at Summerslam 1990, and teaming with him at the [[Survivor Series (1990)|1990 Survivor Series]], along with [[Jim Duggan|\"Hacksaw\" Jim Duggan]] and [[Fred Ottman|Tugboat]], to defeat Earthquake's team.\n\n==== Singles competition (1990&ndash;1993) ====\nIn the fall of 1990, Boss Man began feuding with [[Bobby Heenan]] and [[The Heenan Family]] after Heenan continually insulted Boss Man's mother. He won a series of matches against Heenan Family members in 1991, including [[Sione Vailahi|The Barbarian]] at the [[Royal Rumble (1991)|Royal Rumble]] and [[Curt Hennig|Mr. Perfect]] (via disqualification) at [[WrestleMania VII]] in an [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]] match, which featured the return of [[Andr\u00e9 the Giant]]. At [[SummerSlam (1991)|SummerSlam]], he defeated [[Jacques Rougeau|The Mountie]] in a Jailhouse Match, a match in which the loser must spend a night in jail. This was the only such match ever held by the promotion. Boss Man then briefly feuded with [[Mike Rotunda|Irwin R. Schyster]].\n\nIn 1992, Boss Man began feuding with [[Kevin Wacholz|Nailz]], an ex-convict character who, in a series of promos aired before his debut, claimed Boss Man had been his abusive Officer in prison, and warned he was seeking revenge. On the May 30 episode of ''[[WWF Superstars]]'', Nailz \u2014 clad in an orange prison jumpsuit \u2014 ran into the ring and attacked Boss Man, handcuffing him to the top rope and repeatedly choking and beating him with the nightstick. Boss Man took time off TV to sell his ([[kayfabe]]) injuries, eventually returning and having a series of matches with Nailz in the latter half of 1992. The feud culminated at [[Survivor Series (1992)|Survivor Series]], when Boss Man defeated Nailz in a [[Professional wrestling match types#(Object) on a Pole match|Nightstick on a Pole match]]. This was the final push for the Boss Man during this run, as he was subsequently used as [[enhancement talent]] against [[Scott Hall|Razor Ramon]], [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], and [[Yokozuna (wrestler)|Yokozuna]] on the house show circuit.\n\nThe Big Boss Man's last [[pay-per-view]] match of this run came at the [[Royal Rumble (1993)|1993 Royal Rumble]], where he lost to [[Bam Bam Bigelow]]. He left the WWF shortly after a [[house show]] in [[Gatineau, Quebec]] defeating [[Doink the Clown]] on March 14.<ref>[http://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=104&bild=1&details=7&liga=3&jahr=1993&seite=2 Big Boss Man's 1993 WWF matches, from]. WrestlingData.com. Retrieved on November 20, 2016.</ref> During the next few months he made appearances in the USWA and SMW. On December 4 he made a one-time return to the WWF as a special guest referee to officiate the main event of a house show in Anaheim, California between Bret Hart and Jeff Jarrett. Boss Man was expected to rejoin the WWF but elected to sign with WCW instead.<ref>[http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/93.htm 1993]. thehistoryofwwe.com</ref>\n\n===Return to All Japan Pro Wrestling (1993)===\nTraylor returned to All Japan in 1993. Due to not owning the Big Boss Man gimmick, he again used his \"Big Bubba\" name but still wore the Big Boss Man attire and carried the nightstick. He returned on July 2 defeating Mighty Inoue in a little over three minutes.<ref>[http://www.purolove.com/ajpw/results/93summeraction.php All Japan Pro Wrestling - \"Summer Action Series 1993\"] purolove.com retrieved on May 4, 2019</ref> As was the case with his previous run, he mainly worked tag matches, often with [[Stan Hansen]], [[Kendall Windham]] or \"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams, but also defeated Mighty Inoue, [[John Hindley|Johnny Smith]] and [[Tamon Honda]] in singles matches. He also had some big one-on-one matches as he lost to Akira Taue on July 29 at the [[Nippon Budokan]]<ref>[https://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=690&page=4&s=1400 AJPW Summer Action Series 1993 - Tag 22] cagematch.net retrieved May 19, 2019</ref> and lost to [[Kenta Kobashi]] on October 14.<ref>[https://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=63063 AJPW October Giant Series 1993 - Tag 13] cagematch.net retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> From November to December, Traylor competed in the 1993 [[World's Strongest Tag Determination League#1993|World's Strongest Tag Determination League]] teaming with Williams where they placed 4th.<ref>[http://www.purolove.com/ajpw/history/rwtl93.php Real World Tag League 1993] purolove.com retrieved May 4, 2019</ref> His last match was on the end of the tour on December 3 teaming with Williams in a losing effort to Giant Baba and Stan Hansen.\n\n===World Championship Wrestling===\n==== Early years (1993&ndash;1995) ====\n{{Unreferenced section|date= September 2015}}\nTraylor returned to the United States to debut for [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW), as \"The Boss\", on the December 18, 1993 episode of ''[[WCW Saturday Night]]'', pinning the International World Champion, [[Rick Rude]], in a non-title match. A face, he received a title match against Rude at [[Starrcade (1993)|Starrcade '93: 10th Anniversary]], but lost. In light of legal complaints from the WWF regarding the similarity of \"The Boss\" to \"Big Boss Man\", Traylor was renamed \"The Guardian Angel\", and wore similar attire to those in the [[Guardian Angels|organization he was named after]]. He feuded with [[Big Van Vader]] for most of 1994. In early 1995, he turned heel, and became again known as \"Big Bubba Rogers\". He defeated [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]] at [[Uncensored 1995|Uncensored]] in 1995.\n\n==== Dungeon of Doom and feud with nWo (1996&ndash;1998) ====\nIn 1996, Rogers joined [[The Dungeon of Doom]]. He feuded with former Dungeon of Doom member [[John Tenta]], and newcomer [[Glacier (wrestler)|Glacier]]. By the end of the year, he had turned on the Dungeon of Doom and joined the [[New World Order (professional wrestling)|nWo]]. His stay in the nWo was brief, with Traylor knocked out by an unknown assailant at the start of the February 17, 1997 edition of Nitro, with Traylor later explaining Eric Bischoff fired him from the nWo while he was temporarily paralyzed.  Traylor returned on September 1, now using his real name and vowing to rip Bischoff's head off. He feuded with the nWo, defeating members such as [[Scott Hall (wrestler)|Scott Hall]], Curt Hennig, and [[Mike Jones (wrestler)|Vincent]]. He formed an alliance with [[The Steiner Brothers]], who also sought DiBiase as their manager. The union abruptly ended when Scott Steiner turned on them to join the nWo in February 1998. After losing his final WCW Nitro match to [[Bill Goldberg]] on the March 30 episode of ''[[WCW Nitro|Nitro]]'', Traylor won his final match defeating Bret Hammer on the following ''Saturday Night'' after that he was sent home and WCW let his contract expire.\n\n===Return to WWF/E===\n====Hardcore Championship pursuit (1998&ndash;2000)====\n{{See also|The Corporation (professional wrestling)|l1=The Corporation}}\n[[File:1999 Big Bossman WWF Smackdown (WWE).jpg|thumb|220px|Big Boss Man on ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'' in 1999]]\nTraylor rejoined the WWF shortly after his WCW release and once again became \"Big Boss Man\". On October 12, 1998, he returned to television with a new look, abandoning his blue police shirt for an all-black [[SWAT]]-style uniform, including a tactical vest and gloves. He served as [[Vince McMahon]]'s bodyguard during his feud with [[Stone Cold Steve Austin]] and his later feud with [[D-Generation X]]. He briefly wore a mask, before his identity was revealed.\n\nBoss Man was one of the first members of McMahon's heel stable, [[The Corporation (professional wrestling)|The Corporation]], and served as a bodyguard for other members, such as Vince's son [[Shane McMahon|Shane]]. While in The Corporation, Boss Man won the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|Tag Team Championship]] with [[Ken Shamrock]], won the [[WWE Hardcore Championship|Hardcore Championship]] four times, and lost to [[The Undertaker]] at [[WrestleMania XV]] in a [[Hell in a Cell]] match. After this match, [[The Undertaker]] hanged him from the roof of the cage (an illusion made possible by a body harness concealed under Traylor's outfit).\n\nIn the WWF's Hardcore division, Boss Man's major feud was with [[Al Snow]], a feud that eventually involved Snow's pet chihuahua, Pepper. At [[SummerSlam (1999)|SummerSlam]], the two had a Falls Count Anywhere match that spilled into the backstage area, the street and, finally, into a nearby bar. Just prior to the match, Snow had set Pepper's [[pet carrier]] near the entranceway. Minutes into the match, Boss Man picked it up, taunted Pepper, struck Snow with the carrier and carelessly tossed it behind him. Commentator [[Jim Ross]] immediately apologized to viewers for the act, and stated that Pepper had been removed from the box before the match.\n\nTwo weeks later, Boss Man kidnapped and ransomed Pepper, arranging a meeting in which he fed Snow a meat dish supposedly made from Pepper's remains. The two settled their feud in a [[Hell in a Cell#Legacy|Kennel from Hell match]] at [[Unforgiven (1999)|Unforgiven]], in which a blue solid steel cage surrounded the ring, itself and ringside surrounded by the chain-link fenced \"cell\". The object of the match was to escape from the cage and the cell while avoiding \"attack dogs\" (which turned out to be disappointingly docile) positioned outside the ring. Snow won the match and retained the Hardcore title, which had been returned to him by [[Davey Boy Smith]], who had defeated Boss Man for it.  Boss Man would later win back the Hardcore title in a triple threat match involving [[Al Snow]] and [[Paul Wight|The Big Show]], and would hold it until January 2000, when he lost it to [[Test (wrestler)|Test]].\n\nBoss Man then feuded with [[Paul Wight|The Big Show]] over the [[WWE World Heavyweight Championship|WWF Championship]]. During the feud, Boss Man showed up at Big Show's father's funeral, made some disrespectful remarks, then chained the casket to the back of his car and drove off. The Big Show attempted to save the coffin by jumping on it, riding it for a few yards before losing his grip and tumbling off, the feud also included a segment in which Boss Man invaded the home of Big Show's mother and forced her on camera to admit her son was born an [[Legitimacy (family law)|illegitimate]] child. Boss Man became the #1 contender for the WWF Championship by defeating [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] on the November 15, 1999 episode of ''Raw''. At [[Armageddon (1999)|Armageddon]], The Big Show defeated him to retain the title and end the feud.\n\n==== Various feuds and departure (2000&ndash;2003) ====\nBoss Man entered the [[Royal Rumble (2000)|2000 Royal Rumble match]], where he eliminated [[Solofa Fatu|Rikishi]] (with the help of five other wrestlers), [[Chyna]] and [[Ron Simmons|Faarooq]], before being eliminated by The Rock.\n\nOn the March 19 episode of ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'', he introduced [[Barry Buchanan|Bull Buchanan]] as his prot\u00e9g\u00e9. They teamed to defeat [[Charles Wright (wrestler)|The Godfather]] and [[D'Lo Brown]] at [[WrestleMania 2000]], and the [[Acolytes Protection Agency]] the next month at [[Backlash (2000)|Backlash]]. On the June 5 ''Raw is War'', after losing to [[The Hardy Boyz]] and subsequently arguing, Boss Man knocked Buchanan out with his nightstick when his back was turned and the team split up.\n\nIn the summer of 2000, Boss Man disappeared from the WWF's primary television shows, wrestling mainly on ''[[WWF Jakked/Metal|Jakked]]'' and ''Heat'', where he had a minor feud with [[Crash Holly]] until suffering a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#L|legit]] injury in January 2001. When he returned on the December 20, 2001 of ''SmackDown!'', he formed a team with [[Booker Huffman|Booker T]], after Vince McMahon ordered him to be Booker's enforcer. On the December 27 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Boss Man and Booker T defeated Stone Cold Steve Austin in a handicap match. On the January 7, 2002 episode of ''Raw'', Boss Man and Booker T were defeated by Austin and The Rock. On the January 17 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Boss Man lost to Diamond Dallas Page. At the [[Royal Rumble (2002)|Royal Rumble]], Boss Man competed in the Royal Rumble match where he was eliminated by [[Rikishi (wrestler)|Rikishi]]. On the January 24 episode of ''SmackDown!'', Boss Man lost to Rikishi. The team quietly split in late January 2002, and Boss Man returned to ''Jakked/Metal'' and ''Heat''. On the February 2 episode of ''Metal'', Boss Man defeated [[Gregory Helms|The Hurricane]]. On the February 9 episode of ''Metal'', Boss Man defeated [[Perry Saturn]]. On the March 23 episode of ''[[WWF Jakked/Metal|WWF Jakked]]'', Boss Man and Mr. Perfect lost to [[The Acolytes Protection Agency|The APA]]. In April, he formed a short-lived tag team with [[Curt Hennig|Mr. Perfect]] after both were [[WWE Draft|drafted]] to the Raw [[WWE Brand Extension|brand]]. On the April 1 episode of ''Raw'', Boss Man and Mr. Perfect lost to [[The Hardy Boyz]]. On the April 14 episode of ''Heat'', Boss Man lost to Bradshaw. On the April 28 episode of ''Heat'', Boss Man defeated [[Crash Holly]]. On the May 12 episode of ''Heat'', Boss Man lost to [[D'Lo Brown]]. On the May 26 episode of ''Heat'', he lost his final WWE match to [[Tommy Dreamer]].\n\nTraylor was assigned to train developmental wrestlers in [[Ohio Valley Wrestling]], before being released from WWE in 2003.\n\n===International Wrestling Association of Japan (2004)===\nTraylor's final matches were in the [[International Wrestling Association of Japan]], where he competed in a tournament for the vacant [[IWA World Heavyweight Championship (IWA Japan)|IWA World Heavyweight Championship]]. He made it to the final by defeating [[Doug Gilbert|Freddie Krueger]] before losing to [[Jim Duggan]].<ref name=Wrestlingdata>{{cite web|title=Big Boss Man|url=http://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=104|accessdate=November 19, 2013|publisher=Wrestlingdata}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTraylor had two daughters, Lacy Abilene Traylor and Megan Chyanne Traylor, and was married to Angela, his childhood sweetheart.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/tremendous-tirades-special-rip-ray-traylor/ |title=Tremendous Tirades Special: RIP Ray Traylor |author=Csonka, Larry |date=September 24, 2004 |website=411mania.com |publisher= |accessdate= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035109/http://411mania.com/wrestling/tremendous-tirades-special-rip-ray-traylor/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTraylor suffered a huge motorcycle accident on his Harley-Davidson in May 2002 after he hit a deer, and was badly injured. He spent a year recovering from his injuries, and he was badly affected by close friend [[Curt Hennig]]'s death in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-VgEhLfEpiQ&t=278s|title=Bruce Prichard Shoots on The Death of Big Boss Man|publisher=[[YouTube|youtube.com]]|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2004, Traylor ran for Commission Chairman for [[Paulding County, Georgia]].<ref name=\"Oliver\">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2004/09/24/642381.html|title=Friends remember Big Bossman\t|author=Oliver, Greg|publisher=[[Qu\u00e9becor M\u00e9dia]]|work=[[Canoe.ca]]|date=September 24, 2004|accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://paulding.com/forum/index.php/topic/11151-ray-traylor-big-boss-man/ IN MEMORY OF RAY TRAYLOR \u2013 \"The Big Boss Man\", by Tammy L. Fincham]. Paulding.com. Retrieved on November 20, 2016.</ref> He was the owner of a [[Dallas, Georgia]] storage company called RWT Enterprises.<ref>[http://www.chamberofcommerce.com/dallas-ga/27649226-rwt-enterprises-inc/ RWT Enterprises profile at]. Chamberofcommerce.com. Retrieved on November 20, 2016.</ref>\n\n===Death and legacy===\nTraylor died of a heart attack on September 22, 2004, aged 41 at his home in [[Dallas, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Clevett|first=Jason|title=Ray \"Big Bossman\" Traylor passes away|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2004/09/23/639653.html|accessdate=September 14, 2015|publisher=Canoe Slam}}</ref> He was posthumously inducted into the WWE Hall of Fame in 2016, with his wife and daughters accepting the award on his behalf.\n\nBig Boss Man appears in video games including ''[[WWF WrestleMania 2000]]'', ''[[WWF SmackDown! 2: Know Your Role]]'' and ''[[WWF No Mercy]]''. He further appears posthumously in ''[[WWE Legends of WrestleMania]]'', ''[[WWE All Stars]]'', ''[[WWE '13]]'', ''[[WWE 2K16]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/inside/2k/wwe-2k16/wwe-2k16-roster-playable-characters-superstars-divas|title=Superstars and Divas featured on WWE 2K16 roster list|publisher=[[WWE|WWE.com]]|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WWE 2K17]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k17/article/wwe-2k17-roster-playable-characters-superstars|title=Superstars to be featured on WWE 2K17 roster|publisher=[[WWE|WWE.com]]|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WWE 2K18]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/section/wwe-2k18/article/wwe-2k18-roster-playable-character-list|title=WWE 2K18 roster: Meet the Superstars joining the list of playable characters|publisher=[[WWE|WWE.com]]|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref> ''[[WWE 2K19]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwe.2k.com/roster/wwe-2k19|title=WWE 2K19 Roster|publisher=[[WWE 2K]]|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref> and in ''[[WWE 2K20]]''.\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**Ranked #'''23''' of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 1992<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi50092.htm|accessdate=August 3, 2009|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated Top 500 \u2013 1992|publisher=Wrestling Information Archive|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813033929/http://100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi50092.htm|archivedate=August 13, 2011}}</ref>\n**PWI ranked him #'''138''' of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the \"PWI Years\" in 2003<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi500yr.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 5, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707054220/http://www.100megsfree4.com/wiawrestling/pages/pwi/pwi500yr.htm |archivedate=July 7, 2011 }}</ref>\n*'''[[Superstars of Wrestling|Pro Wrestling This Week]]'''\n**Wrestler of the Week (May 3\u20139, 1987)<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Pro Wrestling This Week |url= |access-date= |series=[[Superstars of Wrestling]] |first=Joe |last=Pedicino |authorlink=Joe Pedicino |first2=Gordon (hosts) |last2=Solie |author2link=Gordon Solie |network=[[Broadcast syndication|Syndicated]] |station=[[WATL]] |location=[[Atlanta, Georgia]] |date=May 9, 1987 |season= |number= |minutes= |transcript= |quote= |language=}}</ref>\n*'''[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Bill Watts)|Universal Wrestling Federation]]'''\n**[[UWF Heavyweight Championship]] ([[UWF Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref>[http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/whtuwf.html Solie's Title Histories:UWF \u2013 UNIVERSAL WRESTLING FEDERATION]. Solie.org (May 30, 1986). 