ne (magazine)|''Fortune'']].<ref>{{cite news|title=Alibaba Named to FORTUNE's World's Most Admired Companies List {{!}} Alizila.com|url=http://www.alizila.com/alibaba-named-fortunes-worlds-admired-companies-list/|work=Alizila.com|date=19 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McClay|first1=Rebecca|title=10 Companies Owned by Alibaba|url=https://www.investopedia.com/insights/10-companies-owned-alibaba/|website=Investopedia|date=25 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt closing time on the date of its [[initial public offering]] (IPO) \u2013 US$25 billion, the world's highest in history \u2013 19 September 2014, Alibaba's market value was US$231 billion.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-alibaba-ipo/alibaba-surges-38-percent-on-massive-demand-in-market-debut-idUSKBN0HD2CO20140919 | title=Alibaba surges 38 percent on massive demand in market debut | last1=Baker | first=Lianna B. | last2=Toonkel | first2=Jessica | last3=Vlastelica |first3=Ryan | editor-last1=Orlofsky | editor-first1=Steve |editor-last2=Adler | editor-first2=Leslie |work=[[Reuters]] | date=September 19, 2014}}</ref> It is one of the top 10 most valuable and is the 59th biggest public companies in the world by Global 2000 list.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.todayonline.com/world/beijings-battle-control-its-homegrown-tech-giants | title=Beijing's battle to control its homegrown tech giants | work=[[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]] | date=24 September 2017}}</ref> In January 2018, Alibaba became the second Asian company to break the US$500 billion valuation mark, after its competitor [[Tencent]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Alibaba market value hits the $500 billion valuation mark | url=https://technode.com/2018/01/25/alibaba-500-million-market-cap/ | first=NICOLE | last=JAO | work=TechNode | date=25 January 2018}}</ref> {{as of|2018||}}, Alibaba has the 9th highest global [[brand valuation]].<ref>{{cite news | title=China Now Has 2 of the Top 10 Most Valuable Brands in the World For the First Time | url=https://fortune.com/2018/05/29/chinese-brands-alibaba-tencent-brandz/ | first=DAVID | last=MEYER | work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] | date=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlibaba is the world's largest retailer and e-commerce company, is on the [[list of largest Internet companies]] and [[artificial intelligence]] companies, is one of the biggest venture capital firms, and one of the biggest investment corporations in the world.<ref>{{cite news | last=McLaughlin | first=Bay | title=This Week In China Tech: Alibaba Brings AI To Pig Farming And Retail Tech On The Rise | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/baymclaughlin/2018/02/14/this-week-in-china-tech-alibaba-brings-ai-to-pig-farming-and-retail-tech-on-the-rise/ | work=[[Forbes]] | date=February 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=McLaughlin | first=Bay | title=This Week In China Tech: Alibaba Buys Chip Maker, Face Scans To Board Planes, And More | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/baymclaughlin/2018/05/02/this-week-in-china-tech-alibaba-buys-chip-maker-face-scans-to-board-planes-and-more/ | work=[[Forbes]] | date=May 2, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last=McLaughlin | first=Bay | title=This Week In China Tech: Alibaba Invests 1 Trillion Yuan And China Battles Against Google's AlphaGo | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/baymclaughlin/2018/05/09/this-week-in-china-tech-alibaba-invests-1-trillion-yuan-and-china-battles-against-googles-alphago/ | work=[[Forbes]] | date=May 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=How Alibaba is using AI to power the future of business | url=https://www.cmo.com.au/article/641280/how-alibaba-using-ai-power-future-business/ | first=JENNIFER | last=O'BRIEN | work=[[International Data Group]] | date=18 May 2018}}</ref> The company hosts the largest B2B (Alibaba.com), C2C ([[Taobao]]), and B2C ([[Tmall]]) marketplaces in the world.<ref>{{cite news |title=Alibaba's Nine Biggest Competitors in Asia |url=https://www.globalfromasia.com/alibaba-competitors/ |work=Global From Asia |date=23 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Alexa Top 500 Global Sites |url=https://www.alexa.com/topsites |work=www.alexa.com |language=en}}</ref> Its online sales and profits surpassed all US retailers (including [[Walmart]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon,]] and [[eBay]]) combined since 2015.<ref name=\"Institutional Investor\">{{cite news|last1=Cheng|first1=Allen|title=Alibaba vs. The World|url=https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/article/b1505pjf8xsy75/alibaba-vs-the-world|accessdate=25 April 2018|publisher=Institutional Investor|date=July 25, 2017}}</ref> It has been expanding into the media industry, with revenues rising by triple percentage points year after year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alibaba generates more revenue than Amazon and eBay combined|url=https://www.rt.com/business/365103-alibaba-revenues-profits-rise/|work=RT International|language=en-EN}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Alibaba Becomes World's Most Valuable Retail Brand {{!}} News {{!}} Apparel Magazine(AM)|url=https://apparelmag.com/alibaba-becomes-worlds-most-valuable-retail-brand|work=apparelmag.com|language=en}}</ref> It also sets the record on the 2018 edition of China's [[Singles' Day]], the world's biggest online and offline shopping day.<ref>{{cite news | last=Pham | first=Sherisse | title=Alibaba Singles Day sales top $30 billion | website=CNN | date=November 10, 2018 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/11/10/tech/alibaba-singles-day/index.html | access-date=November 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Tech in Asia - Connecting Asia's startup ecosystem|url=https://www.techinasia.com/china-singles-day-2017-record-spending|work=www.techinasia.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsit.gr/texnologia/alibaba-poliseis-molis-23-dis-dolarion-tis-protes-9-ores-tis-meras-ton-singles/2912953/|title=Alibaba: \u03a0\u03c9\u03bb\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03bc\u03cc\u03bb\u03b9\u03c2\u2026 23 \u03b4\u03b9\u03c3. \u03b4\u03bf\u03bb\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 9 \u03ce\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \"\u03bc\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd singles\"!|last=|first=|date=11 November 2019|work=NewsIt|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Naming ==\nThe company's name came from the character [[Ali Baba]] from the [[Middle Eastern]] folk tale collection ''[[One Thousand and One Nights]]'' because of its universal appeal.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2014/05/06/alibabas-ipo-filing-everything-you-need-to-know/ | title=Alibaba's IPO Filing: Everything You Need to Know | first=Stephen | last=Grocer | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=7 May 2014 | url-access=subscription}}</ref> As [[Jack Ma]], one of the founders, explained:{{quote|\nOne day I was in San Francisco in a coffee shop, and I was thinking Alibaba is a good name. And then a waitress came, and I said, \"''Do you know about Alibaba?''\" And she said ''yes''. I said, \"''What do you know about him?''\", and she said, \"[[Open Sesame (phrase)|''Open Sesame'']]\". And I said, \"''Yes, this is the name!''\" Then I went on to the street and found 30 people and asked them, \"''Do you know Alibaba?''\" People from India, people from Germany, and people from Tokyo and China ... they all knew about Alibaba. Alibaba \u2013 open sesame. Alibaba is a kind, smart business person, and he helped the village. So ... easy to spell, and globally known. Alibaba opens sesame for small- to medium-sized companies. We also registered the name \"Ali[[Mama and papa|mama]]\", in case someone wants to marry us!\"<ref name=\"naming\">{{cite web| url=http://www.wordlab.com/2007/10/where-did-alibaba-the-brand-name-come-from/ |title=Where did Alibaba, the brand name, come from? |work=Wordlab |date=15 October 2007 }}</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20070227023026/[http://resources.alibaba.com/topic/19446/Where_did_Alibaba_the_brand_name_come_from_.htm \u2013 The original forum post referred to in the wordlab article; it does ''not'' appear to have been posted by Alibaba staff]</ref>}}\n\n==History==\nOn 4 April 1999, [[Jack Ma]] and his team of 17 friends and students founded Alibaba.com, a China-based [[Business-to-business|B2B]] marketplace site, in his [[Hangzhou]] apartment. In October 1999, Alibaba received a US$25 million investment from [[Goldman Sachs]] and [[SoftBank Group|SoftBank]]. Alibaba.com was expected to improve the domestic e-commerce market and perfect an [[Ecommerce platform|E-Commerce platform]] for Chinese enterprises, especially [[small and medium-sized enterprises]] (SMEs), to help export Chinese products to the global market as well as address [[World Trade Organization]] (WTO) challenges. In 2002, Alibaba.com became profitable three years after launch. Ma wanted to improve the global e-commerce system, so from 2003 onward, Alibaba launched [[Taobao|Taobao Marketplace]], [[Alipay]], Alimama.com, and Lynx.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hottopics.ht/stories/consumer/jack-ma-the-man-leading-the-chinese-e-commerce-market/|title=Jack Ma: The man leading the Chinese e-commerce market|last=Popovic|first=Stevan|date=May 4, 2014|work=Hot Topics}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.alibabagroup.com/en/about/history|title=Alibaba Group |website=www.alibabagroup.com|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[eBay]] announced its expansion into China in 2003, Ma viewed the American company as a foreign competitor and rejected eBay's buyout of Alibaba's subsidiary Taobao. Through applying existing technologies and gaining trust in the Chinese e-commerce market, as well as expanding through dominating the market at a loss before making a return on additional services, Alibaba's subsidiaries outperformed eBay in the Chinese e-commerce market, claiming a growing percentage of consumers from eBay. Alibaba subsidiary Taobao would later force eBay out of the Chinese market, with eBay closing its unprofitable China Web unit, though the two companies would break even six years later.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/business-insider/alibaba-jack-ma-life-story.html|title=The Rags-to-Riches Life Story of Alibaba Founder Jack Ma|date=2017-03-02|website=Inc.com|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/quicktake/alibaba|title=Quicktake - Alibaba|last=Chen|first=Lilu Yilun|date=19 November 2017|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, [[Yahoo!]] invested in Alibaba through a [[variable interest entity]] (VIE) structure, buying a 40% stake in the company for US$1 billion.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> This would as a result net in US$10 billion in Alibaba's IPO alone to Yahoo!.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nAccording to Li Chuan, a senior executive at Alibaba, the company was planning in 2013 to open traditional brick and mortar retail outlets in partnership with Chinese real estate company [[Wanda Group]].<ref name=\"hsu2013\">{{cite web |work=BrightWire News |url=http://bw-original-reporting.tumblr.com/post/54526405940/alibaba-to-open-brick-and-mortar-stores-in-wanda-plazas |title=Alibaba to Open Brick and Mortar Stores in Wanda Plazas Across China | last=Hsu | first=Alex | date=3 July 2013 |url-status=dead | archivedate=13 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013150400/http://bw-original-reporting.tumblr.com/post/54526405940/alibaba-to-open-brick-and-mortar-stores-in-wanda-plazas }}</ref> Additionally, Alibaba purchased a 25% stake in Hong Kong-listed Chinese department store chain Intime Retail in early 2014.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Mozur | first1=Paul | first2=Esther | last2=Fung | title=Alibaba to Pay $692 Million for Stake in Intime Retail | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/alibaba-to-pay-692-million-for-35-stake-in-intime-retail-1396234141 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=31 March 2014 | url-access=subscription}}</ref> In early 2017, Alibaba and Intime's founder Shen Guojun agreed to pay as much as HK$19.8 billion (US$2.6 billion) to take the store chain private. Alibaba's stake\u201428% from 2014's US$692 million investment\u2014would rise to about 74% after the deal.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Lin | first1=Liza | first2=Nathan | last2=Becker | date=January 10, 2017 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/alibaba-seeks-to-take-intime-private-with-founder-1484005494 | title=Alibaba Bags Chinese Retailer Intime in $2.6 Billion Deal | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2014, Alibaba, [[Coatue Management]], and [[Andreessen Horowitz]] led a US$250 million Series D financing round that was completed by [[Transportation network company|on-demand transportation company]] [[Lyft]], bringing its total amount raised to $332.5 million.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/04/02/lyft-250m/|title=Lyft Raises $250 Million From Coatue, Alibaba, And Third Point To Expand Internationally|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref> On 5 June 2014, Alibaba bought a 50% stake of [[Guangzhou Evergrande Taobao F.C.|Guangzhou Evergrande F.C.]] from [[Evergrande Real Estate|Evergrande Real Estate Group Ltd.]] in a deal that was worth 1.2 billion yuan (US$192 million).<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-06-05/evergrande-rises-on-alibaba-soccer-stake-report-hong-kong-mover|title=Alibaba Buys Into Soccer Team After Billionaires' Drinks|date=5 June 2014|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref> On 5 September 2014, the group\u2014in a regulatory filing with the [[US Securities and Exchange Commission]]\u2014set a [[United States dollar|US$]]60- to $66- per-share price range for its scheduled [[initial public offering]] (IPO), the final price of which would be determined after an international roadshow to gauge the investor interest in Alibaba shares to shareholders. On 18 September 2014, Alibaba's IPO priced at US$68, raising US$21.8&nbsp;billion for the company and investors. Alibaba was the biggest US IPO in history, bigger than Google, Facebook, and Twitter combined.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Assessing Attitudes Toward Content and Design in Alibaba's Dry Goods Business Infographics|journal = Journal of Business and Technical Communication|volume = 31|pages = 30\u201362|language=en|doi=10.1177/1050651916667530|year = 2017|last1 = Zhang|first1 = Yuejiao}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Alibaba's IPO Priced at $68 a Share | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/alibabas-ipo-priced-at-68-a-share-1411075675 | first1=Telis | last1=Demos | first2=Matt | last2=Jarzemsky | date=18 September 2014 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Alibaba prices at $68, becomes top U.S. IPO |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/markets/2014/09/18/alibaba-deal-price-ipo/15846185/|date=18 September 2014|accessdate=18 September 2014|newspaper=USA Today}}</ref> On 19 September 2014, Alibaba's shares (BABA) began trading on the NYSE at an opening price of $92.70 at 11:55&nbsp;am EST. On 22 September 2014, Alibaba's underwriters announced their confirmation that they had exercised a [[greenshoe option]] to sell 15% more shares than originally planned, boosting the total amount of the IPO to $25 billion.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-09-22/alibaba-s-banks-said-to-increase-ipo-size-to-record-25-billion.html|title=Alibaba's Banks Boost IPO Size to Record of $25 Billion|date=22 September 2014|work=Bloomberg L.P.|last2=Chen|first2=Lulu Yilun |last1=Picker|first1=Leslie|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Alibaba IPO ranks as world's biggest after additional shares sold | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-alibaba-ipo-value-idUSKCN0HH0A620140922 | first=Elzio | last=Barreto\n| work=[[Reuters]] | date=September 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Alibaba and the [[International Olympic Committee]] jointly announced an $800 million deal that would last till 2028 in where the company would sponsor the [[Olympic Games]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-01-19/alibaba-will-put-its-technology-to-the-test-on-an-olympian-stage|title=Alibaba Olympics Sponsorship Deal Said to Be Worth $800 Million|date=19 January 2017|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref> In September 2018, Jack Ma, the main founder of Alibaba, announced that he would step down as chairman in a year's time so he could focus on philanthropy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2018/09/15/china-will-struggle-to-produce-another-jack-ma|title=China will struggle to produce another Jack Ma|work=The Economist|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref> In response to the announcement, ''[[The Economist]]'' stated that Ma had a significant impact in China and worldwide via contributions and dedication to various businesses.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/leaders/2018/09/15/china-will-struggle-to-produce-another-jack-ma|title=China will struggle to produce another Jack Ma|work=The Economist|access-date=2018-09-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Bloomberg cited sources familiar with the matter as saying that Alibaba was considering raising $20 billion through a second listing in Hong Kong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-05-27/alibaba-is-said-to-weigh-raising-20-billion-via-second-listing|title=Alibaba Weighs Raising $20 Billion Through A Second Listing|website=Bloomberg|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> On Tuesday, 10 September 2019, Jack Ma officially stepped down as the chairman of Alibaba, [[Daniel Zhang]] succeeded him at the head of the company. In September 2019, the municipal government of Hangzhou announced that it was boosting its monitoring of the private sector by embedding government officials in Alibaba and other companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-09-23/china-steps-up-government-presence-at-alibaba-private-giants|title=China Boosts Government Presence at Alibaba, Private Giants|last=Chen|first=Lulu Yilun|date=September 23, 2019|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|access-date=September 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/24/business/china-government-officials-companies/index.html|title=China is sending government officials into companies like Alibaba and Geely|last=He|first=Laura|date=September 24, 2019|work=[[CNN]]|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Companies and affiliated entities==\n\n=== E-commerce and retail service platforms ===\n[[File:Alibaba group Headquarters.jpg|thumb|Alibaba group Headquarters]]\n[[File:Alibaba Binjiang Park.jpg|thumb|240px|Alibaba [[Binjiang District|Binjiang]] Campus in Hangzhou, headquarters for Alibaba's B2B service.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alibaba Subsidiary Aboub B2B Marketplace|url=https://www.aboub.com/|website=ABOUB|accessdate=11 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111100025/https://www.aboub.com/|archive-date=11 November 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>|alt=]]In 1999, Jack Ma launched the primary business of Alibaba, Alibaba.com, while working as an English teacher in Hangzhou. Alibaba.com later became the world's largest online [[business-to-business|B2B]] trading platform for small businesses as of 2014.<ref>{{cite news | title=Alibaba Flexes Muscles Before IPO | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/alibaba-flexes-muscles-ahead-of-ipo-1397605974 | first1=Juro | last1=Osawa | first2=Paul | last2=Mozurand | first3=Rolfe | last3=Winkler | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=April 15, 2014 | url-access=subscription}}</ref> Alibaba.com has three main services: the English language portal Alibaba.com, which handles sales between importers and exporters from more than 240 countries and regions,<ref name=home>{{cite web | title=Alibaba Group | url=https://www.alibabagroup.com/en/global/home | work=Alibaba Group Group}}</ref> the Chinese portal 1688.com, which manages domestic B2B trade in China, and transaction-based retail website [[AliExpress]].com(\u5168\u7403\u901f\u5356\u901a), which allows smaller buyers to buy small quantities of goods at wholesale prices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/usa/373133-trump-alibaba-ceo-meet/|title=Open Sesame? Trump & Alibaba CEO Jack Ma talk of creating 1mn US jobs|website=RT International}}</ref> Alibaba.com went public at the Hong Kong Stock Exchange in 2007, and was delisted again in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alibaba Group Said to Plan Privatizing Alibaba.com Close to IPO Price|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-02-17/alibaba-said-to-plan-to-take-alibaba-com-private-for-close-to-ipo-price.html|website=Bloomberg L.P.|accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> In 2013, 1688.com launched a direct channel that was responsible for $30&nbsp;million in daily transaction value.<ref name=\"hsu0713\">{{cite web |work=BrightWire News |url=http://bw-original-reporting.tumblr.com/post/55694392054/alibabas-1688-com-launches-new-direct-channel |title=Alibaba's 1688.com Launches New Direct Channel, Responsible for 30 Million USD Per Day in Transactions Value | last=Hsu | first=Alex | date=17 July 2013 | url-status=dead | archivedate=13 October 2013 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013134423/http://bw-original-reporting.tumblr.com/post/55694392054/alibabas-1688-com-launches-new-direct-channel }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Alibaba launched [[Taobao|Taobao Marketplace]] (\u6dd8\u5b9d\u7f51), offering a variety of products for retail sale. Taobao grew to become China's largest [[Customer to customer|C2C]] online shopping platform and later became the second most visited web site in China, according to [[Alexa Internet]].<ref name=\"einhorn2013\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-01-15/alibabas-jack-ma-is-moving-on-with-an-ipo-looming|title=Alibaba's Jack Ma Is Moving On, With an IPO Looming|website=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|publisher=Bruce Einhorn|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Alexa.com-taobao\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/taobao.com|title=Taobao's Alexa Statistics|work=Alexa.com|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref> Taobao's growth was attributed to offering free registration and commission-free transactions using a free third-party payment platform.<ref name=\"newschinamag1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newschinamag.com/magazine/from-stall-to-mall|title=From Stall to Mall|last=Zhe|first=Sun|date=January 2012|work=News China|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140925203642/http://www.newschinamag.com/magazine/from-stall-to-mall|archivedate=25 September 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Advertising made up 75 percent of the company's total revenue, allowing it to break even in 2009. In 2010, Taobao's profit was estimated to be \u00a51.5&nbsp;billion (US$235.7&nbsp;million), which was only about 0.4 percent of their total sales figure of \u00a5400&nbsp;billion (US$62.9&nbsp;billion) that year, way below the industry average of 2 percent, according to iResearch estimates.<ref name=\"newschinamag1\" /> According to Zhang Yu, the director of Taobao, between 2011 and 2013, the number of stores on Taobao with annual sales under \u00a5100&nbsp;thousand increased by 60%; the number of stores with sales between \u00a510&nbsp;thousand and \u00a51&nbsp;million increased by 30%, and the number of stores with sales over \u00a51&nbsp;million increased by 33%.<ref name=\"hsu0713b\">{{cite web|url=http://bw-original-reporting.tumblr.com/post/55694291348/alibabas-taobao-continues-to-attract-new-stores|title=Alibaba's Taobao Continues to Attract New Stores, Focuses on Personalized Services, Store Branding and Customized Contracts|last=Hsu|first=Alex|date=17 July 2013|work=BrightWire News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013140057/http://bw-original-reporting.tumblr.com/post/55694291348/alibabas-taobao-continues-to-attract-new-stores|archivedate=13 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, Taobao introduced a spin-off, [[Tmall|Taobao Mall]] (\u6dd8\u5b9d\u5546\u57ce, later Tmall.com), an online retail platform to complement the Taobao [[Customer to customer|C2C]] portal, offering global brands to an increasingly affluent Chinese consumer base. It became the eighth most visited web site in China as of 2013.<ref name=\"Alexa.com-tmall\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/tmall.com|title=Alexa Web Site Statistics for Tmall.com|work=Alexa.com|publisher=Alexa.com|accessdate=18 October 2013}}</ref> In 2012, Tmall.com later changed its Chinese name to Tianmao (\u5929\u732b, \"sky cat\"), reflecting off of Tmall's Chinese pronunciation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.people.cn/90778/7702962.html|title=Tmall changes its name for better positioning - People's Daily Online|website=en.people.cn|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref> In March 2010, Taobao launched the group shopping website Juhuasuan (\u805a\u5212\u7b97), offering \"flash sales\", which are products that are available at a discount for only a fixed time period. In October 2010, Taobao beta-launched eTao, a [[comparison shopping website]] that offers search results from mostly Chinese online shopping platforms,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenextweb.com/asia/2010/10/13/microsoft-and-alibaba-launch-search-engine-etao-in-china/|title=Microsoft and eTao|website=The Next Web|accessdate=10 December 2015|date=13 October 2010}}</ref> including product searches, sales and coupon searches. According to the Alibaba Group web site, eTao offers products from Amazon China, [[Dangdang]], Gome, [[Yihaodian]], [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] China, and Vancl, as well as Taobao and Tmall.<ref name=home/> As part of a restructuring of Taobao by Alibaba, these spin-offs became separate companies in 2011, with Tmall and eTao becoming separate businesses in June and Juhuasuan becoming a separate business later in October.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://money.cnn.com/2011/06/17/technology/taobao_split/index.htm | title=Alibaba splits Taobao into three parts | last=Pepitone | first=Julianne | work=[[CNN]] | date=June 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Alibaba launched [[AliExpress]].com, an online retail service made up of mostly small Chinese businesses offering products to international online buyers. It is the most visited [[Ecommerce platform|E-Commerce platform]] in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internetretailer.com/commentary/2014/09/09/alibaba-tops-e-commerce-sites-russia-well-china|title=Alibaba tops e-commerce sites in Russia as well as China|author=Adrien Henni|date=2014-09-09|publisher=Internetretailer.com|accessdate=2017-05-09}}</ref> It allows small businesses in China to sell to customers all over the world, resulting in a wide variety of products. It might be more accurate to compare AliExpress to eBay, though, as sellers are independent; it simply serves as a host for other businesses to sell to consumers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/us-money-blog/2014/sep/23/alibaba-human-hair-american-women-ecommerce|title=Why Alibaba is a success in the US: its market for human hair extensions nets American women in its weave|last=Kasperkevic|first=Jana|date=2014-09-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-05-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Similar to eBay, sellers on Aliexpress can be either companies or individuals. It connects directly Chinese businesses with buyers. The main difference from Taobao is that it's aimed primarily at international buyers, mainly in USA, Russia, Brazil or Spain.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gooali.com/blogs/aliexpress/82661636-jack-ma-su-inspiradora-historia|title=Jack Ma: Su inspiradora historia|last=GOOALI\u00ae|work=GOOALI\u00ae|access-date=2017-05-05|language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Alibaba and six large Chinese logistics companies (including SF Express) established a company called [[Cainiao]] for delivery of packages in China. This network gradually grew to 14 local logistics companies in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Cynthia |title=One Platform to Rule Them All: The Brains Behind Cainiao Network (PI) |url=https://ecommerceiq.asia/cainiao-logistics-southeast-asia/ |website=E Commerce Asia |publisher=E COm Asia |accessdate=17 December 2018|date=7 December 2016 }}</ref> In 2016, Alibaba's [[Taobao]] and [[Tmall]], two of the world's largest and most popular online retail marketplaces, achieved a total transaction volume of 3 trillion yuan (US$478.6 billion). The company aims to double the transaction volume to 6 trillion yuan by 2020. {{as of|2018|February|}}, Taobao reached 580 million [[monthly active users]], while Tmall achieved 500 million monthly active users.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://expandedramblings.com/index.php/taobao-statistics/|title=22 Amazing Taobao Statistics|date=19 January 2017|website=DMR}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://expandedramblings.com/index.php/tmall-statistics/|title=18 Amazing Tmall Statistics|date=19 February 2017|website=DMR}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/alibaba-achieves-3-trillion-yuan-transaction-volume-milestone/|title=Alibaba achieves 3 trillion yuan transaction volume milestone {{!}} ZDNet|last1=Lee|first1=Cyrus|work=ZDNet|language=en}}</ref> It is also rapidly expanding its e-commerce network abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-alibaba-cainiao-investment/alibaba-takes-control-of-logistics-business-pledges-15-billion-to-expand-network-idUSKCN1C10C2|title=Alibaba takes control of logistics business, pledges $15 billion to expand network|last1=Wu|first1=Kane|last2=Cadell|first2=Cate|date=September 26, 2017|editor=Muralikumar Anantharaman|website=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> Alibaba has also announced that it will invest 100 billion yuan over five years to build a global logistics network, underpinning an aggressive overseas expansion, and demonstrating Alibaba's commitment to building the most efficient logistics network in [[China]] and around the world. It is investing a further 5.3 billion yuan in [[Cainiao]] Logistics to boost its stake to 51 percent from 47 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alibabagroup.com/en/news/article?news=p170926|title=Alibaba to Take Majority Stake in Cainiao Network|date=2017-09-26|website=Alibaba Group|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171003041151/http://www.alibabagroup.com/en/news/article?news=p170926|archive-date=2017-10-03|url-status=|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref> The investment would value Cainiao, a joint venture of top Chinese logistics firms, at around US$20 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/alibaba-takes-control-of-logistics-business|title=Alibaba takes control of logistics business|last=hermes|date=27 September 2017|website=The Straits Times}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|11Main}} On 11 June 2014, Alibaba launched US shopping site 11 Main. The 11 Main marketplace hosts more than 1,000 merchants in categories such as clothing, fashion accessories and jewelry as well as interior goods and arts and crafts and it plans to keep adding more, said the company.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/alibaba-launches-u-s-shopping-site-11-main-1402469675 | title=Alibaba Tackles Amazon, eBay on Home Turf | first=Juro | last=Osawa | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=11 June 2014 | url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-27790367|title=BBC News \u2013 China's Alibaba plans US online shop|publisher=bbc.com|accessdate=11 July 2014|work=BBC News|date=11 June 2014}}</ref> On 23 June 2015, Alibaba announced that it is selling 11 Main to OpenSky, an online-marketplace operator based in New York.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/alibaba-sells-u-s-subsidiary-11-main-to-opensky-1435027883 | title=Alibaba Stumbles in U.S. Online Market | first1=Juro | last1=Osawa | first2=Eva | last2=Dou | date=23 June 2015 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n[[File:Lazada Laguna warehouse.jpg|thumb|[[Lazada Group|Lazada]] warehouse in [[Cabuyao, Laguna]], Philippines during the company's 11.11 sale promotion in 2018. Lazada Group is a subsidiary of Alibaba Group and Alibaba co-founder [[Peng Lei|Lucy Peng Lei]] is [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of the company.]]\nIn April 2016, Alibaba announced that it intended to acquire a controlling interest in [[Lazada Group|Lazada]] by paying $500 million for new shares and buying $500M worth of shares from existing investors.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-04-12/alibaba-to-pay-1-billion-for-control-of-lazada-e-commerce-site | title=Alibaba Expands in Southeast Asia With $1 Billion Lazada Deal | first1=Lulu Yilun | last1=Chen | first2=Selina | last2=Wang | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> Lazada Group is a Singaporean e-commerce company founded by Rocket Internet in 2011. Lazada operates sites in Indonesia, [[Malaysia]], the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam. Its sites launched in March 2012, with a business model of selling inventory to customers from its own warehouses. In 2013 it added a marketplace model that allowed third-party retailers to sell their products through Lazada's site. Lazada features a wide product offering in categories ranging from consumer electronics to household goods, toys, fashion and sports equipment. In March 2018, Alibaba announced its plan to invest an additional $2 billion in the company, totaling a $4 billion investment. Alibaba also plans to appoint Alibaba co-founder [[Peng Lei|Lucy Peng]] as Lazada's new CEO.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/19/alibaba-invests-addition-2-billion-dollars-in-e-commerce-firm-lazada.html|title=Alibaba invests additional $2 billion in Southeast Asian e-commerce firm Lazada|last=Choudhury|first=Saheli Roy|date=2018-03-19|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-03-20}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2016, Alibaba launched Alitrip, later named Fliggy, an online travel platform that is designed as an online mall for brands such as airline companies and agencies.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.phocuswire.com/Fliggy-the-online-travel-platform-you-probably-havent-heard-of | title=Fliggy, the online travel platform you (probably) haven't heard of | first=Linda | last=Fox | work=[[Phocuswire]] | date=July 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.chinatravelnews.com/article/120020 | title=5 reasons why travel brands need to take notice of Alibaba's Fliggy | work=ChinaTravelNews | date=January 26, 2018}}</ref> Fliggy set the target audience as younger generation and it strives to become a one-stop service when they plan their trips, particularly in overseas travel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inboundreport.com/2017/07/11/alibaba-relaunches-travel-site-as-fliggy-to-compete-with-ctrip/|title=Alibaba Relaunches Travel site as Fliggy to Compete with CTrip|website=Inbound Reporter|publisher=Tom Berrigan|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref> On 7 August 2017, Alibaba Group and [[Marriott International]] hotel group announced a comprehensive strategic co-operation. Two companies will set up a joint venture company. Through the docking technology system and the superiority resources, Fliggy has Marriott hotel flagship store. It has the same function with Marriott Chinese website and Marriott mobile app to create the best global travel experience for consumers.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.travelpulse.com/news/hotels-and-resorts/marriott-targets-chinese-travelers-via-alibaba.html | title=Marriott Targets Chinese Travelers via Alibaba | last=POLING | first=MONICA | work=[[TravelPulse]] | date=August 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Alibaba started opening a chain of supermarkets, named Hema (\u76d2\u9a6c, lit. box horse), as part of the company's \"new retail strategy,\" where customers can either order in the store or online for delivery in under 30 minutes. It offers a mobile app that recommends customers products based on data analytics.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/18/alibaba-hema-stores-blend-online-and-offline-retail.html | title=Alibaba Hema stores blend online and offline retail | last=Choudhury | first=Saheli Roy | work=[[CNBC]] | date=July 18, 2017}}</ref> In addition, customers can have their groceries cooked to eat in the food court of the supermarket.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/chinas-hema-market-has-two-advantages-over-amazon-go-2018-2 | title=China has a supermarket unlike anything in the US \u2014 and it has 2 major advantages over Amazon Go | last=Peterson | first=Hayley | work=[[Business Insider]] | date=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Cloud computing and artificial intelligence technology ===\nIn conjunction with the company's 10th anniversary, Alibaba launched [[Alibaba Cloud]] in September 2009, aiming to build a cloud computing service platform, including e-commerce data mining, e-commerce data processing, and data customization.<ref name=home/> It has R&D centres and operators in Hangzhou, Beijing, Hong Kong, Singapore, Silicon Valley<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aliyun.com/about/?spm=5176.383338.25.1.rpQhdR|title=aliyun.com}}</ref> and Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atimes.com/article/alibaba-clouds-global-expansion-program-rolls-dubai/|title=Alibaba Cloud's global expansion program rolls into Dubai|last=Wanxia|first=Lin|date=22 November 2016|website=www.atimes.com|access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref> In July 2014, Alibaba Cloud entered into a partnership deal with Inspur. Alibaba Cloud is the largest high-end cloud computing company in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cloudwedge.com/2014-aliyun-inspur-partner-to-beat-cloud-competition/|title=Aliyun & Inspur Partner to Beat Cloud competition|date=7 July 2014}}</ref> In 2009, Alibaba acquired HiChina, the largest domain registration service and web hosting service company in China, and built it into Alibaba Cloud.<ref name=\"HiChina\">{{cite news|url=http://news.netcraft.com/archives/2015/05/27/aliyun-cloud-growth-makes-alibaba-largest-hosting-company-in-china.html|title=Aliyun cloud growth makes Alibaba largest hosting company in China|last1=Mutton|first1=Paul|date=May 27, 2015|accessdate=17 August 2016|publisher=Netcraft}}</ref> On 28 July 2011, Alibaba Cloud released [[AliOS]] (formerly ''Yun OS'' and ''Aliyun OS''), a [[Linux distribution]] designed for mobile devices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/is-aliyun-os-really-linux-android-a-rip-off-of-both/|title=Is Aliyun OS really Linux? Android? A rip-off of both?|first=Steven J.|last=Vaughan-Nichols|website=ZDNet}}</ref> In the 2017 Computing Conference in Hangzhou, Alibaba launched [[AliGenie]], a China-based open-platform intelligent personal assistant. It is currently used in the [[Tmall Genie]] smart speaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://technode.com/2017/08/11/alibabas-first-consumer-targeting-artificial-intelligence-speaker-genie-x1-unveils/|title=Alibaba's AI-powered speaker hits the shelves \u00b7 TechNode|date=11 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 27, 2019, Alibaba unveiled a [[64-bit computing|64-bit]] [[RISC-V]] [[Central processing unit|processor]] called the XuanTie 910 (Black Iron 910). It is a [[14 nanometer|12 nm]] [[Multi-core processor|16-core]] with a clockrate of 2.5&nbsp;GHz, and was designed by Alibaba's subsidiary T-Head (also known as Pingtouge). Alibaba claim the Xuantie 910 is up to 40% faster than other RISC-V cores and is capable of 7.1 Coremark/MHz.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tomshardware.com/news/alibaba-risc-v-cpu-processor-xuantie-910,40027.html|title=Alibaba Unveils Open Source RISC-V CPU Amid US-China Trade War|date=2019-07-26|website=Tom's Hardware|language=en|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://syncedreview.com/2019/07/25/alibaba-is-open-sourcing-its-powerful-new-risc-v-processor-for-5g-and-ai/|title=Alibaba Is Open-Sourcing Its Powerful New RISC-V Processor for 5G and AI|last=Synced|date=2019-07-25|website=Synced|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/07/27/alibaba_risc_v_chip/|title=Alibaba sketches world's 'fastest' 'open-source' RISC-V processor yet: 16 cores, 64-bit, 2.5GHz, 12nm, out-of-order exec|last=Quach|first=Katyanna|date=27 July 2019|website=The Register|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 2019, Alibaba announced an [[AI accelerator]] called the Hanguang 800. The Hanguang 800 contains 17 billion transistors built with a [[14 nanometer|12 nm]] process and was designed by T-Head and DAMO Academy (Alibaba's research arm). Alibaba claim it is capable of 78,563 images per second (IPS) inference and 500 IPS/W in ResNet-50. The Hanguang 800 will be available to be rented on [[Alibaba Cloud]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-alibaba-chip-idUSKBN1WA09R|title=Alibaba unveils self-developed AI chip for cloud computing services|date=2019-09-25|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-09-27|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://syncedreview.com/2019/09/25/alibabas-new-ai-chip-can-process-nearly-80k-images-per-second/|title=Alibaba's New AI Chip Can Process Nearly 80K Images Per Second|last=Synced|date=2019-09-25|website=Synced|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/25/alibaba-unveils-its-first-ai-chip-called-the-hanguang-800.html|title=Alibaba unveils its first A.I. chip as China pushes for its own semiconductor technology|last=Kharpal|first=Arjun|date=2019-09-25|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\n=== FinTech and online payment platforms ===\n[[File:Alipay payment 20160121.jpg|thumb|Food ordered with [[Alipay]]]]\nIn 2004, the Alibaba Group launched [[Alipay]], a third-party online payment platform with no transaction fees. It also provides an [[escrow]] service, in which buyers can verify whether they are happy with goods they have bought before releasing money to the seller.<ref name=\"newschinamag1\" /> Alibaba Group [[Corporate spin-off|spun off]] Alipay in 2010 in a controversial move.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qz.com/221635/alibaba-has-a-new-way-of-explaining-its-controversial-alipay-spinoff/|title=Alibaba has a new way of explaining its controversial Alipay spinoff|last=Guilford|first=Gwynn|date=June 2014|work=Quartz}}</ref> According to analyst research report, Alipay has the biggest market share in China with 300&nbsp;million users and control of just under half of China's online payment market in February 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefinancialist.com/not-just-a-paypal-clone-chinas-internet-giants-chart-their-own-course/|title=China's Internet Giants Lead in Online Finance|author=John Watling|date=14 February 2014|work=The Financialist|publisher=Credit Suisse|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219223010/http://www.thefinancialist.com/not-just-a-paypal-clone-chinas-internet-giants-chart-their-own-course/|archivedate=19 February 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=15 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2013, Alipay launched a financial product platform called Yu'ebao (\u4f59\u989d\u5b9d).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/channels/news/financial-innovation-china-alibaba%E2%80%99s-leftover-treasure-%E4%BD%99%E9%A2%9D%E5%AE%9D-234236|title=Financial Innovation in China: Alibaba's Leftover Treasure \u2013 \u4f59\u989d\u5b9d|last=Chohan|first=Usman W.|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref> In 2015, Alibaba announced that they will introduce a system that can be paid by recognizing the owner's face.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.naver.com/main/hotissue/read.nhn?mid=hot&sid1=105&cid=993859&iid=987890&oid=003&aid=0006409123&ptype=021 |script-title=ko:\uc54c\ub9ac\ubc14\ubc14, \uc54c\ub9ac\ud398\uc774\uc5d0 '\uc5bc\uad74 \uc778\uc2dd' \uacb0\uc81c \ub3c4\uc785|date=March 17, 2015|work=[[Newsis]]|accessdate=October 12, 2017|location=Seoul |language=Korean|trans-title=Alibaba introduces 'Face Recognition' payment to AliPay}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wu|first=Jen-Her|last2=Li|first2=Qi|last3=Wei|first3=Kwok Kee|date=2016-07-02|title=Alibaba's IT platform and electronic commerce synergy in driving \"Singles' Day\"|journal=Journal of Organizational Computing and Electronic Commerce|volume=26|issue=3|pages=193\u2013202|doi=10.1080/10919392.2016.1194050|issn=1091-9392}}</ref> On 16 October 2014, the Alipay company was re-branded as [[Ant Financial|Ant Financial Services]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-alibaba-idUSKCN0I50KJ20141016|title=Alibaba affiliate Alipay rebranded Ant in new financial services push|date=2014-10-16|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-01-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOne of the factors for Alibaba's success in this platform is the company's quick and reliable payment system, where it offers several types of payment systems such as [[credit card]], [[debit card]], Alipay, [[UnionPay|Quick-pay]], and [[online banking]]. These payment systems help to cope with simultaneous cash flow transactions with ease and convenience. [[Ant Financial]] was ranked sixth in Fortune's ''Change the World'' list, recognized for the positive green environmental impact of its ''Ant Forest'', the world's largest platform for tracking individuals' carbon footprints. Ant Financial and its partners have achieved considerable success in the reduction of {{CO2}} emissions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/tech/2017-09/09/content_31776061.htm|title=Ant Financial ranked 6th in Fortune environmental list|last=Wang|first=Yanfei|date=2017-09-09|work=China Daily|access-date=2017-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170912165319/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/tech/2017-09/09/content_31776061.htm|archive-date=2017-09-12|url-status=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.ce.cn/main/latest/201709/11/t20170911_25884165.shtml|title=Ant Financial named in Fortune's \"Change the World\" list--China Economic Net|work=en.ce.cn|access-date=11 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170911204434/http://en.ce.cn/main/latest/201709/11/t20170911_25884165.shtml|archive-date=11 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Ant Financial is the highest valued [[fintech]] company in the world, and the world's most valuable [[Unicorn (finance)|unicorn (start-up) company]], with a valuation of US$150 billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/05/29/chinas-ant-financial-raises-10-billion-at-150-billion-valuation.html|title=China's Ant Financial reportedly raises $10 billion at $150 billion valuation|work=CNBC|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ywang/2018/05/28/ant-financial-said-to-close-150-b-funding-round/#25b95be37dcc|title=Ant Financial Said To Close $150B Funding Round|last1=Wang|first1=Yue|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/business/21726713-ant-financial-500m-customers-home-plans-expand-chinas-digital-payments-giant-keeps|title=China's digital-payments giant keeps bank chiefs up at night|work=The Economist|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>\n\n=== Entertainment services ===\nAlibaba created a new live entertainment business unit under its '''Digital Media and Entertainment Group''' which focuses on ticketing, content creation and live experiences, bringing its entertainment ticketing platform ''Damai'' and its content creation and technology units ''MaiLive'' and ''Maizuo'' under one roof. It aims to provide a platform for live events (e.g. [[concert]]s, [[Play (theatre)|plays]], [[eSports]] and [[sport]]s events), as well as supporting content partners and leveraging Alibaba's data capability for offline shows.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://technode.com/2017/09/20/alibaba-live-entertainment-business-group/|title=Alibaba announces live entertainment business group - TechNode|date=20 September 2017|work=TechNode}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.investopedia.com/news/alibaba-launches-unit-dedicated-live-events/|title=Alibaba Launches Unit Dedicated to Live Events|last1=Fuscaldo|first1=Donna|date=20 September 2017|work=Investopedia}}</ref> It also provides the online digital distribution service 9Apps, which hosts downloadable content and applications.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://inc42.com/buzz/alibaba-ucweb-data-theft/|title=Alibaba Owned UCWeb Faces Risk Of Ban For Data Theft Allegations|work=inc42.com}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2014, Alibaba agreed to acquire a controlling stake in [[Alibaba Pictures|ChinaVision Media Group]] for $804&nbsp;million. The two firms announced they would establish a strategic committee for potential future opportunities in online entertainment and other media areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-chinavision-alibaba/alibaba-buys-chinavision-stake-for-804-million-gains-tv-movie-content-idUSBREA2B02C20140312|title=Alibaba buys ChinaVision stake for $804&nbsp;million; gains TV, movie content|last1=Kwok|first1=Donny|last2=Thomas|first2=Denny|date=March 12, 2014|editor=Edwina Gibbs|website=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=October 12, 2017|last3=Carsten|first3=Paul}}</ref> The company was renamed Alibaba Pictures Group.<ref name=\"WSJ - ChinaVision\">{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/spoiler-alert-jack-ma-beats-jet-li-but-no-hollywood-ending-for-alibaba-1510821204 | title=Spoiler Alert: Jack Ma Beats Jet Li, but No Hollywood Ending for Alibaba | last=Yuan | first=Li | date=November 16, 2017 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | url-access=subscription}}</ref> In March 2015, Alibaba Group launched [[AliMusic]] as its music division. Xiami Music and Tiantian Music are two of music steaming APP owned by AliMusic. AliMusic named [[Gao Xiaosong]] as the chairman and Song Ke as Chief Executive Officer in July 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.alizila.com/alibaba-names-renowned-musician-gao-xiaosong-run-music-unit-2/|title=Alibaba Names Renowned Musician Gao Xiaosong to Run Music Unit {{!}} Alizila.com|date=2015-07-20|work=Alizila.com|access-date=2018-03-02|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2017, [[Tencent]] Music has expected $10bn IPO by signing a rights deal with Alibaba, strengthening its position within the important Chinese market. Under the terms of the deal Alibaba will gain the right to stream music from international labels such as [[Sony Music]], [[Universal Music Group]] and [[YG Entertainment]], which already have exclusive deals with Tencent, in return for offering to its catalogue from [[Rock Records]], [[HIM International Music]] and so on.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://technode.com/2017/09/12/alibaba-and-tencent-collaborate-on-music-copyright/|title=Alibaba and Tencent collaborate on music copyright \u00b7 TechNode|date=2017-09-12|work=TechNode|access-date=2018-03-02|language=en-US}}</ref> In April 2014, Alibaba and Yunfeng Capital, a private equity company controlled by Alibaba's founder, Jack Ma, agreed to acquire a combined 18.5 percent stake in [[Youku Tudou]], which broadcasts a series of popular television programs and other videos over the Internet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/04/28/alibaba-buying-stake-in-youku-tudou-a-chinese-web-tv-company-for-1-2-billion/?_php=true&_type=blogs|title=Alibaba Buys Stake in Chinese Web TV Company for $1.2 Billion|author=Neil Gough|date=April 28, 2014|website=New York Times}}</ref>\n\n=== Internet services ===\nIn 2004, the Alibaba Group released Aliwangwang, an instant messaging software service for interactions between customer and online sellers. By 2014, there are 50 million Aliwangwang users, making it the second largest instant messaging tool in China.<ref>{{cite web|last=Yan |first=Sophia |url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/06/11/technology/alibaba-ucweb/index.html |title=Alibaba continues quest to own the Chinese Internet - Jun. 11, 2014 |publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=2014-06-11 |accessdate=2017-05-09}}</ref> In October 2013, the Alibaba's chairman [[Jack Ma]] announced that the Alibaba Group would no longer use [[Tencent]]'s messaging application [[WeChat]], and would henceforth promote its own messaging application and service, Laiwang.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.scmp.com/news/china-insider/article/1337869/jack-ma-delete-wechat-account-favour-own-baby-laiwang|title=Alibaba's Jack Ma to dump WeChat service in favour of 'own baby' Laiwang|work=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=23 October 2013|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> In April 2014, Alibaba Group and [[UCWeb]], a Chinese provider of mobile internet software technology and services, launched [[Shenma]] (\u795e\u9a6c), a mobile-only search engine, as part of a [[joint venture]].<ref>[http://www.marketwatch.com/story/alibaba-ucweb-plan-mobile-search-joint-venture-2014-04-28 Alibaba, UCWeb plan mobile-search joint venture], ''MarketWatch'', Apr 28, 2014</ref><ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/russellflannery/2014/04/28/alibaba-ucweb-team-up-in-mobile-search/ Alibaba, UCWeb Team Up In Mobile Search], ''Forbes'' magazine, Apr 28. 2014</ref> Later in June, the Alibaba Group acquired UCWeb, with an international product portfolio that includes a mobile browsing service (UC Browser), app and game distribution platforms (9Apps and 9Game), a mobile traffic platform (UC Union) and [[UC News]] that primarily caters to all types of news in the India market (as an aggregator) among others.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/06/11/us-alibaba-group-ucweb-idUSKBN0EM04P20140611 Alibaba to buy out UCWeb in China's biggest internet merger], ''Reuters'', June 11, 2014</ref><ref>[https://www.forbes.com/sites/jlim/2014/06/11/alibaba-fully-buys-out-ucweb-in-chinas-biggest-internet-deal-ever/ Alibaba Fully Buys Out UCWeb in China's Biggest Internet Deal Ever], ''Forbes'' magazine, June 11, 2014</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/alibaba-buys-remaining-stake-in-ucweb-1402456416 | title=Alibaba Buys Remaining Stake in UCWeb | first=Paul | last=Mozur | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=June 11, 2014 | url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-06-11/alibaba-to-acquire-rest-of-ucweb-to-boost-its-mobile-offerings.html Alibaba to Acquire Rest of UCWeb to Boost Mobile Offering], ''Bloomberg'', June 11, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.pcworld.com/article/2362820/ucweb-to-accelerate-international-expansion-after-alibaba-merger.html UCWeb to accelerate international expansion after Alibaba merger], ''PCWorld'', June 12, 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.ejinsight.com/20140613-alibabas-final-piece-of-the-puzzle-ucweb/ UCWeb \u2014 The final piece of Alibaba's puzzle], ''HongKong Economic Journal'', Jun 13, 2014</ref> Alibaba's Y Projects Business Unit developed the Xuexi Qiangguo app, which is used to teach [[Xi Jinping Thought]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Alibaba is the force behind hit Chinese Communist Party app: sources |first=Pei |last=Li |first2=Cate |last2=Cadell |work=[[Reuters]] |date=February 18, 2019 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-alibaba-government-idUSKCN1Q70Y7 |editor-first=Muralikumar |editor-last=Anantharaman}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2005, Alibaba Group formed a strategic partnership with [[Yahoo!]] and acquired Yahoo! China, a Chinese portal previously launched on 24 September 1999 that focuses on Internet services like news, email, and search.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-08/11/content_468249.htm | title=Alibaba acquires Yahoo China | agency=[[Xinhua News Agency]] | publisher=[[China Daily]] | date=August 11, 2005}}</ref> In April 2013, Alibaba Group announced that, as part of the agreement to buy back the Yahoo! Mail stake, that they would suspend technological support for China Yahoo! Mail service and begin migration of Yahoo! China Mail accounts. Several options were offered to users to make the transition as smooth as possible, and Yahoo! China users had four months to migrate their accounts to the Aliyun mail service, the [[Yahoo! Mail]] service in the United States, or to another third-party e-mail provider of the user's choice.<ref>Steadman, Ian. (22 April 2013) [https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2013-04/22/yahoo-china-email Yahoo! decides to close its Chinese mail service (Wired UK)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130831235656/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2013-04/22/yahoo-china-email |date=31 August 2013 }}. Wired.co.uk. Retrieved on 21 September 2013.</ref> Yahoo! China closed its mail service on 19 August 2013. E-mails sent to Yahoo! China accounts could be forwarded to an Alimail box until 31 December 2014. Users were also allowed to transfer e-mail accounts to yahoo.com or any other e-mail service. It is estimated there are no more than a million users with Yahoo! Mail for China and chances are they also own other e-mail accounts.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://technode.com/2013/08/19/yahoochina-closing-mail-service-today/ | title=Yahoo!China Closing Mail Service Today | first=TRACEY | last=XIANG | work=TechNode | date=19 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Others ===\nIn 2014, Alibaba and Yunfeng Capital, a private equity firm, launched AliHealth when the two companies bought a 54% stake in [[CITIC 21CN]] for HK$1.33&nbsp;billion (US$171&nbsp;million).<ref name=\"SCMP-20140125\">{{cite news | last1=Chan | first1=Ray | last2=Yiu | first2=Enoch | last3=Yu | first3=Sophie | title=Alibaba buys controlling stake in Citic 21CN | url=https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/1412886/alibaba-buys-controlling-stake-citic-21cn | work=[[South China Morning Post]] | date=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1=Wang | first1=Jasmine | title=Alibaba, Yunfeng to Buy Control of Citic 21CN for $171 Million | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-01-23/alibaba-yunfeng-to-buy-control-of-citic-21cn-for-171-million | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=23 January 2014}}</ref> It is listed on the [[Hong Kong Stock Exchange]] as {{Sehk|0241}}. It positions itself as a pharmaceutical e-commerce business and medical services. In the same year, Alibaba acquired Chinese map supplier [[AutoNavi]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-04-11/alibaba-agrees-to-buy-autonavi-in-1-5-billion-mapping-deal | title=Alibaba Agrees to Buy AutoNavi in $1.5 Billion Map Deal | work=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=April 11, 2014}}</ref> In April 2015, the group also reached an agreement to transfer its online B2C pharmacy, Tmall Medical (yao.Tmall.com), to AliHealth. The integration provides consumers a wide range of pharmaceutical and health products available in China.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.scmp.com/tech/e-commerce/article/1831701/alibabas-healthcare-subsidiary-aims-expand-e-commerce-operations | title=Alibaba's healthcare subsidiary aims to expand e-commerce operations despite losses | first=Bien | last=Perez | work=[[South China Morning Post]] | date=2 July 2015}}</ref> In 2015, Alibaba later launched its [[Shanghai]]-based sports division, AliSports, after a consolidation of some of the parent company's existing business units.<ref name=alisports>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=325404250|title=Company Overview of Alisports.com|date=17 July 2017|website=Bloomberg|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170717171746/https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=325404250|archivedate=17 July 2017|url-status=live|accessdate=17 July 2017}}</ref> The new company's operations encompass television and digital sports rights, event operation, venue commercialization, copyright, media, business development, gaming, and ticketing.<ref name=alisports/> AliSports secured exclusive title sponsorship of the [[FIFA Club World Cup]] from 2015 to 2022.<ref name=\"sbs-2016\">{{cite news |url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2016/11/19/infantino-suggests-32-team-fifa-club-world-cup|title=Infantino suggests 32-team FIFA Club World Cup|date=19 November 2016|work=Special Broadcasting Service|accessdate=17 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119174716/http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2016/11/19/infantino-suggests-32-team-fifa-club-world-cup|archivedate=19 November 2016|url-status=live|location=Sydney}}</ref> The company announced a Champion of Champions [[rugby sevens]] tournament in 2017, to be played in Shanghai for the highest prize money ever offered in the sport.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.scmp.com/sport/rugby/hk-sevens/article/2102972/china-host-richest-ever-rugby-sevens-tournament-us100-million |title=China to host richest ever rugby sevens tournament as US$100 million injection bears first fruit|date=17 July 2017|work=South China Morning Post|accessdate=17 July 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170717164656/http://www.scmp.com/sport/rugby/hk-sevens/article/2102972/china-host-richest-ever-rugby-sevens-tournament-us100-million|archivedate=17 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Alibaba agreed to acquire the ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' and other media assets belonging to the group for a consideration of $266 million. Although Alibaba promised editorial independence, vice-chairman [[Joseph Tsai]] said that Alibaba believes that \"the world needs a plurality of views when it comes to China coverage. China's rise as an economic power and its importance to world stability is too important for there to be a singular thesis.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.techinasia.com/jack-ma-big-mistake |title=Disconnect: Jack Ma made a big mistake buying SCMP |last=Custer |first=C. |website=Tech in Asia |date=December 14, 2015 |accessdate=October 12, 2017}}</ref> The acquisition attracted media concerns over what this would mean for the newspaper's coverage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-scmp-group-alibaba/alibaba-agrees-to-266-million-acquisition-deal-with-south-china-morning-post-idUSKBN0TX01S20151214 |title=Alibaba agrees on $266&nbsp;million acquisition deal with South China Morning Post |last1=Jourdan |first1=Adam |last2=Kwok |first2=Donny |last3=Yu |first3=Jess Macy |date=December 14, 2015 |editor-last1=Roantree |editor-first1=Anne Marie |editor-last2=Woo |editor-first2=Ryan |work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nOther subsidiaries of Alibaba include Hangzhou Ali Venture Capital and Alibaba Entrepreneurs Fund. Hangzhou Ali Venture Capital (\u676d\u5dde\u963f\u91cc\u521b\u4e1a\u6295\u8d44) is a company 80% owned by [[Jack Ma]] and another manager of Alibaba. For regulatory purpose, Alibaba Group did not own the company directly, but by [[pleading]]. It was considered as a subsidiary and/or consolidated entity of Alibaba Group.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1577552/000119312514184994/d709111dex211.htm | title=List of Significant Subsidiaries and Consolidated Entities of Alibaba Group Holding Limited | work=Alibaba Group | publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]}}</ref> Ali Venture Capital is a shareholder of [[Beijing Enlight Media]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://disclosure.szse.cn/finalpage/2016-04-12/1202163197.PDF | title=2015 Annual Report|date=2016|access-date=22 January 2017 | work=Beijing Enlight Media |publisher=[[Shenzhen Stock Exchange]] | language=Chinese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202030810/http://disclosure.szse.cn/finalpage/2016-04-12/1202163197.PDF|archive-date=2 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and a [[A-share (mainland China)|domestic shareholder]] of [[China Unicom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://static.sse.com.cn/disclosure/listedinfo/announcement/c/2017-08-21/600050_20170821_12.pdf |script-title=zh:\u975e\u516c\u5f00\u53d1\u884cA\u80a1\u80a1\u7968\u9884\u6848 |date=21 August 2017|access-date=25 August 2017|publisher=China United Network Communications| language = zh-hans}}</ref> The Alibaba Entrepreneurs Fund is a non-profit making initiative launched by Alibaba Group in 2015.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.scmp.com/tech/start-ups/article/2113126/alibabas-entrepreneurs-fund-eyes-next-billion-dollar-start-hong-kong | title=Alibaba's entrepreneurs fund eyes next billion-dollar start-up in Hong Kong | first=Bien | last=Perez | work=[[South China Morning Post]] | date=September 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.techinasia.com/companies/alibaba-entrepreneurs-fund | title=Alibaba Entrepreneurs Fund (\u963f\u91cc\u5df4\u5df4\u521b\u4e1a\u8005\u57fa\u91d1) | publisher=[[Tech in Asia]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.afr.com/work-and-careers/careers/sydneys-luke-grana-backed-by-alibaba-entrepreneurs-fund-20161003-grtofu | title=Sydney's Luke Grana backed by Alibaba Entrepreneurs Fund | first=Michael | last=Bailey | work=[[The Australian Financial Review]] | date=October 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlibaba also has invested in more than 10 startups in [[Hong Kong]] including DayDayCook,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.scmp.com/tech/start-ups/article/2102566/daydaycook-raises-100-million-yuan-series-b-funding | title=DayDayCook raises fresh funds to enhance step-by-step instructional videos on recipes | last=Zen | first=Soo | work=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=July 15, 2017}}</ref> [[GoGoVan]],<ref>{{cite news | url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/01/gogovan-becomes-hong-kongs-first-1-billion-startup-following-merger-deal/ | title=GoGoVan becomes Hong Kong's first $1 billion startup following merger deal | first=Jon | last=Russell | work=[[TechCrunch]] | date=September 2, 2017}}</ref> WeLend<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.techinasia.com/welend-wolaidai-welab-alibaba-funding|title=Alibaba funds lending startup WeLab to help it break out of China |last=Steven|first=Millward |work=[[Tech in Asia]] | date=November 8, 2017}}</ref> and Qupital.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/samameen/2017/05/17/alibaba-makes-its-first-fintech-investment-in-hong-kong/ | title=Alibaba Makes Its First FinTech Investment In Hong Kong | last=Sam | first=Ameen | work=[[Forbes]] | date=May 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/17/qupital-raises-2-million/|title=Hong Kong's Qupital raises $2M led by Alibaba to finance invoice loans for SMEs|last=Jon|first=Russell|date=2017-05-18|website=Techcrunch|access-date=}}</ref> In 2019, Alibaba launched a China-Russia flights in collaboration with [[Russian Post]] to assure fast shipping of products.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-alibaba-russia-flights-idUSKBN1XH1LX | title=Alibaba, Russian Post launch China-Russia flights to cut delivery times | first1=Anton | last1=Zverev | first2=Nadezhda | last2=Tsydenova | work=[[Reuters]] | date=November 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Corporate governance==\n[[File:Enabling eCommerce- Small Enterprises, Global Players (39008130265) (cropped).jpg|thumb|[[Jack Ma]], founder and the former executive chairman of the Alibaba Group|alt=]]Alibaba's main co-founder [[Jack Ma]] is the former [[Chairman|executive chairman]] of the Alibaba Group from its creation to 10 September 2019. The current executive chairman is [[Daniel Zhang]], who succeeded Ma on 10 September 2019, and is also Alibaba's [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] since 2015. [[Joseph Tsai]] is Alibaba's executive vice-chairman since 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/alibabas-ceo-replaced-2015-5 | title=Alibaba's CEO replaced | last1=Kelley | first1=Michael B. | last2=Yarow | first2=Jay | work=[[Business Insider]] | date=7 May 2015}}</ref> [[J. Michael Evans]] is Alibaba's president since 2015.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/alibaba-group-names-michael-evans-as-president-1438682344 | title=Alibaba Group Names Michael Evans as President | last=Wong | first=Gillian | date=August 4, 2015 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | issn=0099-9660 | url-access=subscription}}</ref> The board of directors of Alibaba includes top management Jack Ma, Joseph Tsai, Daniel Zhang, and J. Michael Evans, directors Eric Jing and [[Masayoshi Son]] (founder and CEO of [[SoftBank Group|SoftBank]]), and independent directors such as Chee Hwa Tung, Walter Kwauk, B\u00f6rje E. Ekholm, and Wan Ling Martello, as well as [[Yahoo!]] co-founder and former CEO [[Jerry Yang]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web | url=https://www.alibabagroup.com/en/about/leadership | title=Alibaba Group: Leadership | publisher=Alibaba Group}}</ref> Besides Ma, Tsai, Zhang, and Evans, senior management also includes Maggie Wu ([[Chief financial officer|CFO]]) Judy Tong ([[Chief human resources officer|CPO]]), Jeff Zhang ([[Chief technology officer|CTO]] and President of [[Alibaba Cloud]] Intelligence), Sophie Wu ([[Chief customer officer|CCO]]), Tim Steinert (General Counsel and Secretary), Jessie Zheng ([[Chief risk officer|CRO]] and CRGO/Chief Platform Governance Officer), Angel Zhao (Head of Alibaba Globalization Leadership Group), Chris Tung ([[Chief marketing officer|CMO]]), Trudy Dai (President of Wholesale Marketplaces), Fan Jiang (President of [[Taobao]].com), and Jet Jing (President of [[Tmall]].com).\n\nPreviously, Jack Ma served as the CEO of the Alibaba Group since its creation, but later stepped down on 2013, choosing [[Jonathan Lu]] as his successor.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.techinasia.com/alibaba-jack-ma-last-ceo-speech/ | title=Jack Ma's Last Speech as Alibaba CEO | last1=Wee | first1=Willis |work=[[Tech in Asia]] | date=13 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/e3aef1dc-5f01-11e2-9f18-00144feab49a.html|title=Jack Ma steps down as Alibaba chief|last1=Hille|first1=Kathrin|date=15 January 2013|work=[[Financial Times]]|accessdate=23 September 2014|location=United Kingdom|url-access=subscription}}</ref> The Alibaba Group under Lu was performing well, though there were rumors that Ma was growing distrustful in Lu's ability to lead the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.techinasia.com/alibaba-new-ceo-jonathan-lu/|title=Alibaba Appoints Jonathan Lu as New CEO, Will Take Ma's Desk on May 10|last1=Millward|first1=Steven|date=11 March 2013|work=Tech in Asia|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/alibaba-prices-ipo-2014-9|title=IT'S OFFICIAL: ALIBABA WILL BE THE LARGEST IPO EVER|last=Udland|first=Myles|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref> [[Daniel Zhang]], who served as [[Chief operating officer|COO]] of Alibaba under Lu, succeeded Lu as CEO in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/russellflannery/2015/05/07/who-is-alibabas-new-ceo/|title=Who Is Alibaba's New CEO?|last=Flannery|first=Russell|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref> On 10 September 2018, Ma chose Zhang to succeed him as executive chairman of the Alibaba Group after his stepping down announcement, and this would go into effect in 1 year on 10 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/10/alibaba-jack-ma-succession-plan-daniel-zhang-to-take-over-as-chairman.html|title=Jack Ma succession plan at Alibaba: Daniel Zhang to become chairman|last=Choudhury|first=Saheli Roy|date=2018-09-09|website=www.cnbc.com|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref> Since 2012, the [[Communist Party of China]] has had a Group Party Committee in place in the company and has over 2,000 party members as Alibaba employees.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bpq2DwAAQBAJ|title=Chinese Communist Espionage: An Intelligence Primer|last=Mattis|first=Peter|last2=Brazil|first2=Matthew|date=2019-11-15|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1-68247-304-7|location=|pages=252|language=en}}</ref> In 2019, the Chinese government began embedding officials inside of major technology companies, including Alibaba.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-09-23/china-steps-up-government-presence-at-alibaba-private-giants|title=China Boosts Government Presence at Alibaba, Private Giants|last=Chen|first=Lulu Yilun|date=September 23, 2019|work=[[Bloomberg News]]|access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Gold Supplier membership===\nAlibaba.com offers a paid Gold Supplier membership to try to ensure that each seller is genuine; sellers' Gold Supplier status and the number of years it has been held are displayed.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.alibaba.com/help/gold_supplier.html |title=Gold Supplier | publisher=Alibaba Group}}</ref> The supplier verification types and checks are listed on Alibaba.com's website, with more stringent checks for sellers outside China.<ref name=goldchecks>{{cite web | url=https://service.alibaba.com/buyer/ab/safety_security/products/verification_services.php | title=Alibaba.com's Supplier Verification Services | publisher=Alibaba Group}}</ref> While the majority of suppliers are reported to be genuine,{{citation needed|date=August 2013}} there have been many cases of sellers, some with Gold Supplier status, seeking to defraud unsuspecting buyers.<ref name=minalto>{{cite web |url=http://andrewminalto.com/top-10-alibaba-scams/ |title=Top 10 Scams on Alibaba.com! |newspaper=Andrewminalto.com |date= January 2014 |author =Andrew Minalto |accessdate= 22 January 2016}}</ref> In February 2011, controversy ensued when Alibaba's corporate office admitted that it had granted the mark of integrity of its \"China Gold Supplier\" program to more than 2,000 dealers that had subsequently defrauded buyers; the firm's share price dropped \"abruptly\" after the announcement.<ref name=thieves>{{cite news | title=Alibaba and the 2,236 thieves | url=https://www.economist.com/business/2011/02/24/alibaba-and-the-2236-thieves | work=[[The Economist]] |date=24 February 2011}}</ref> A statement from the firm reported that Yan Limin, the general manager of Alibaba.com at the time, had been dismissed in March for \"misconduct\"; Phil Muncaster of UK's ''The Register'' additionally reported that \"a further 28 employees had been involved in dodgy dealings\".<ref>{{cite news | title=Ex-Alibaba GM cuffed as bribery scandal resurfaces | url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/07/06/alibaba_general_manager_arrested_bribery | last=Muncaster | first=Phil | work=[[The Register]] |date=6 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs the ''Economist'' noted, the company's response has conflicting components: Alibaba's promulgated view that its corrective actions indicate its commitment to quality and integrity (where it contrasts itself with other scandal-associated Chinese business sectors), ''versus'' a damage control view suggesting that the subscription-driven, third-party verified \"China Gold Supplier\" program was endangered by diminished trust in its endorsement system, removing the incentive for global buyers to choose Alibaba as their business-to-business service, thus more broadly endangering Alibaba through impact on its brand and capabilities (the latter via the \"defenestration of senior people\").<ref name=thieves/> The scandal was said to have placed the head of Alibaba Group, Jack Ma\u2014who was described as having been furious over the scandal\u2014in a position to personally fight to win back trust.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/2011/0411/features-jack-ma-alibaba-e-commerce-scandal-face-of-china.html |title=Alibaba's Jack Ma Fights To Win Back Trust |last=Epstein |first=Gady |journal=Forbes |date=11 April 2011 |accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Uranium sales===\nIn May 2012, a US law enforcement agent posing as an American broker representing persons in [[Iran]] posted an advertisement on Alibaba.com seeking to purchase [[uranium]]. In August 2013, Patrick Campbell of [[Sierra Leone]] was arrested at New York's [[John F. Kennedy International Airport]]. Samples of raw uranium ore were allegedly found concealed in the soles of his shoes. Campbell was accused of seeking to arrange the export of 1,000 tonnes of [[yellowcake]] from Sierra Leone to the Iranian port of [[Bandar Abbas]], packed in drums and disguised as the mineral [[chromite]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-23825972 | title=Iran nuclear: 'Uranium shoe' man arrested in US | work=[[BBC News]] | date=24 August 2013}}</ref> It was later determined that the samples contained an insignificant amount of uranium, and Campbell was acquitted at trial.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-09-11/uranium-sting-homeland-security-caught-smuggler-or-created-one | title=The Uranium Sting: Did Homeland Security Catch a Smuggler or Create One? | first=Stuart A. | last=Reid | work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] | date=September 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Counterfeit items and scams===\nAlibaba is frequently associated with fraudulent import of counterfeit items: in 2016, the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]] added Taobao back onto a list of notorious counterfeit platforms that includes the likes of torrent site [[The Pirate Bay]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Why Alibaba Can't Complain About Its Return to the 'Notorious' Counterfeit Market List | url=https://fortune.com/2016/12/22/alibaba-taobao-counterfeit-goods-platform/ | first=SCOTT | last=CENDROWSKI | work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] | date=22 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nAlibaba denied wrongdoing and started timid action against counterfeiters with only two lawsuits filed {{as of|2017|January|4|lc=y|df=US}},<ref>{{cite news | title=Alibaba sues sellers of counterfeit good for the first time after it was blacklisted by the US | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/01/04/alibaba-sues-sellers-of-counterfeit-goods-for-the-first-time-after-it-was-blacklisted-by-the-us.html | first=Arjun | last=Kharpal | work=[[CNBC]] | date=4 January 2017}}</ref> but brands suffering from the counterfeit products continue to blame Alibaba for not doing what it takes to fight the issue.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brands accuse Alibaba of not doing enough to stop sale of counterfeit goods | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/brands-accuse-alibaba-of-not-doing-enough-to-stop-sale-of-counterfeit-goods-1475898037 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] | date=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Class action on IPO===\nAlibaba and the underwriters of its IPO were sued in California in a consolidated [[class action]] lawsuit.<ref name=climbed>{{cite news | url=https://www.capitalwatch.com/article-3272-1.html | title=Alibaba Enters into a $75 Million Settlement Deal; Shares Climbed 2% in Pre-market | work=capitalwatch.com}}</ref> The lawsuit was brought in [[San Mateo County, California|San Mateo]] Superior Court in October 2015 on behalf of investors who purchased Alibaba's [[American Depositary Share]]s, and it alleged violations of the [[Securities Act]].<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/31/stocks-making-the-biggest-moves-premarket-amzn-db-vz-googl--more.html</ref> Alibaba reached a settlement agreement in December 2018, subject to court approval, in which it agreed to pay $75 million to settle the lawsuit.<ref name=climbed/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1577552/000110465918075203/a18-42169_1ex99d1.htm | title=Alibaba Group Enters into Settlement of Securities Act Class Action Initiated in October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://images.law.com/contrib/content/uploads/documents/407/1682/Alibaba-settlement.pdf | title=Alibaba settlement | date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Variable interest entity]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Alibaba Group}}\n* {{Official website}}\n{{Finance links\n| name      = Alibaba Group Holding Ltd\n| google    = BABA\n| yahoo     = BABA\n| bloomberg = BABA:US\n| symbol    = BABA\n| sec_cik   = 1577552\n}}\n{{Alibaba Group|state=expanded}}\n{{Major Internet companies}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Alibaba Group| ]]\n[[Category:Chinese companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Chinese brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Hangzhou]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Silver Lake Partners companies]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in China]]\n[[Category:2014 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Electric vehicle manufacturers of China]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Alibaba}}\n{{short description|Hangzhou-based group of Internet-based e-commerce businesses}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{coord|30.189602|N|120.190371|E|type:landmark_region:CN-33_source:Gaode|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Alibaba Group Holding Limited\n| native_name = \u963f\u91cc\u5df4\u5df4\u96c6\u56e2\u63a7\u80a1\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8\n| logo = Alibaba-Group-Logo.svg\n| logo_caption = \n| image = TaobaoCity Alibaba Xixi Park.jpg\n| image_caption = \"Taobao City\", the main corporate campus for Alibaba Group at Xixi, Hangzhou.\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{ubl|{{nyse|BABA}}|{{hkex|9988}}}}\n| ISIN = US01609W1027\n| industry = [[Technology company]]  \n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1999|04|04|df=yes}}<br />[[Hangzhou]], [[Zhejiang]]\n| founder = [[Jack Ma]] \n| location = No. 969 West Wen Yi Road<ref>{{cite web| title=Our offices | url=https://www.alibabagroup.com/en/contact/offices | publisher=Alibaba Group |language=en}}</ref>\n| location_city = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Yuhang District]], [[Hangzhou]], [[Zhejiang]]\n}}\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = {{plainlist|\n* [[Daniel Zhang]],<br/><small>([[Chairman#Executive chairman|executive chairman]] and [[CEO]])</small>\n* [[Joseph Tsai]],<br/><small>([[Vice Chairman|executive vice chairman]])</small>\n* [[J. Michael Evans]], <small>([[President (corporate title)|president]])</small>\n}}\n| products = {{hlist|[